00:16:53,823 --> 00:16:55,051
Read it.

262
00:16:55,258 --> 00:16:57,317
I know you'll love it.

263
00:16:58,828 --> 00:17:00,591
The whole purpose ofplaces
like Starbucks...

264
00:17:00,830 --> 00:17:03,264
...is for people with no
decision-making ability whatsoever...

265
00:17:03,499 --> 00:17:07,162
...to make six decisions
just to buy one cup of coffee.

266
00:17:07,403 --> 00:17:09,428
Short, tall, lite, dark...

267
00:17:09,672 --> 00:17:11,401
...caf, decaf...

268
00:17:11,607 --> 00:17:12,437
...low-fat, nonfat...

269
00:17:13,609 --> 00:17:15,076
...et cetera.

270
00:17:15,578 --> 00:17:17,273
Mocha frappuccino grande.

271
00:17:17,513 --> 00:17:19,913
So people who don't know
what the hell they're doing...

272
00:17:20,116 --> 00:17:22,983
...or who on earth they are
can, for only $2.95...

273
00:17:23,185 --> 00:17:25,312
...get notjust a cup of coffee...

274
00:17:25,521 --> 00:17:29,184
...but an absolutely
defining sense of self.

275
00:17:30,426 --> 00:17:31,586
Tall.

276
00:17:31,794 --> 00:17:32,818
Decaf.

277
00:17:33,029 --> 00:17:34,257
Cappuccino.

278
00:17:34,463 --> 00:17:36,192
Tall decaf cappuccino.

279
00:17:57,887 --> 00:17:59,218
Bummer.

280
00:18:01,390 --> 00:18:03,551
A Fox Books Superstore.

281
00:18:03,859 --> 00:18:06,157
Quel nightmare.

282
00:18:06,362 --> 00:18:08,762
It has nothing to do with us.
It's big...

283
00:18:08,998 --> 00:18:10,022
...impersonal...

284
00:18:10,232 --> 00:18:13,429
...overstocked and full
of ignorant salespeople.

285
00:18:13,736 --> 00:18:15,397
But they discount.

286
00:18:15,605 --> 00:18:17,596
But they don't provide any service.

287
00:18:17,840 --> 00:18:19,171
We do.

288
00:18:19,375 --> 00:18:20,672
So really...

289
00:18:20,876 --> 00:18:22,537
...it's a good development.

290
00:18:22,745 --> 00:18:25,805
You know how in the flower district
there are all those flower shops...

291
00:18:26,015 --> 00:18:27,642
...so you can find whatever you want?

292
00:18:27,850 --> 00:18:28,714
Well...

293
00:18:28,918 --> 00:18:31,716
...this is going to be
the book district.

294
00:18:31,921 --> 00:18:33,445
If they don't have it, we do.

295
00:18:34,724 --> 00:18:36,021
And vice versa.

296
00:18:36,292 --> 00:18:37,281
Absolutely.

297
00:18:41,030 --> 00:18:43,260
When you are finished
with Fox Books...

298
00:18:43,466 --> 00:18:46,799
...The Shop Around The Corner
is going to be responsible...

299
00:18:47,036 --> 00:18:51,234
...for reversing the entire course
of the lndustrial Revolution.

300
00:18:51,440 --> 00:18:54,238
Well, now, that is so sweet.

301
00:18:54,443 --> 00:18:57,173
Thank you. That is so sweet.

302
00:18:57,380 --> 00:18:58,210
Although l--

303
00:18:58,414 --> 00:18:59,244
What?

304
00:18:59,448 --> 00:19:01,177
Wait a minute.
What is that doing here?

305
00:19:01,384 --> 00:19:02,715
Oh, my gosh...

306
00:19:02,885 --> 00:19:04,409
...this is amazing.

307
00:19:04,620 --> 00:19:05,814
Listen.

308
00:19:07,790 --> 00:19:10,088
The Olympia Report Deluxe Electric.

309
00:19:10,393 --> 00:19:11,382
Report.

310
00:19:11,661 --> 00:19:12,992
As in gunshot.

311
00:19:13,229 --> 00:19:15,789
-That sound is familiar.
-Listen to this.

312
00:19:16,732 --> 00:19:18,290
What, that whirring?

313
00:19:18,567 --> 00:19:20,797
The gentle, soothing lullaby...

314
00:19:21,003 --> 00:19:23,563
...of a piece of machinery so perfect--

315
00:19:23,773 --> 00:19:25,934
I know where I've heard that before.

316
00:19:27,643 --> 00:19:28,541
I needed a backup.

317
00:19:28,744 --> 00:19:30,803
Don't you have another one of these
at your apartment?

318
00:19:31,013 --> 00:19:32,913
-I might!
-That you wrote a column about?

319
00:19:33,115 --> 00:19:34,082
Who cares?

320
00:19:35,151 --> 00:19:36,516
What were you going to say?

321
00:19:36,752 --> 00:19:37,650
-When?
-Before.

322
00:19:37,853 --> 00:19:38,683
Nothing.

323
00:19:39,588 --> 00:19:40,418
Come on.

324
00:19:42,658 --> 00:19:46,094
I'm just wondering.
I'm wondering about my work.

325
00:19:47,596 --> 00:19:49,894
I mean, what is it that I do, exactly?

326
00:19:50,099 --> 00:19:51,623
All I really do is--

327
00:19:51,834 --> 00:19:53,426
All you really do...

328
00:19:53,636 --> 00:19:55,831
...is this incredibly noble thing.

329
00:19:56,038 --> 00:19:56,868
I don't know.

330
00:19:57,106 --> 00:19:59,336
Really, I'm just--

331
00:20:00,376 --> 00:20:01,934
You are a lone reed.

332
00:20:03,713 --> 00:20:05,203
You are a lone...

333
00:20:07,016 --> 00:20:08,210
...reed...

334
00:20:08,451 --> 00:20:09,941
...standing...

335
00:20:10,152 --> 00:20:11,585
...tall...

336
00:20:11,787 --> 00:20:13,778
...waving boldly...

337
00:20:14,290 --> 00:20:16,520
...in the corrupt sands...

338
00:20:16,726 --> 00:20:18,125
...of commerce.

339
00:20:21,464 --> 00:20:22,829
I am a lone reed.

340
00:20:25,000 --> 00:20:27,901
I am a lone reed.

341
00:20:33,976 --> 00:20:36,570
Sometimes I wonder about my life.

342
00:20:36,912 --> 00:20:39,176
I lead a small life.

343
00:20:39,548 --> 00:20:41,516
Well, valuable, but small.

344
00:20:41,717 --> 00:20:43,378
And sometimes I wonder...

345
00:20:43,586 --> 00:20:45,713
...do I do it because I like it?

346
00:20:45,921 --> 00:20:48,355
Or because I haven't been brave?

347
00:20:49,158 --> 00:20:52,650
So much of what I see reminds me
of something I read in a book...

348
00:20:52,862 --> 00:20:55,160
...when, shouldn't it be
the other way around?

349
00:20:56,031 --> 00:20:57,430
I don't really want an answer.

350
00:20:57,666 --> 00:21:01,363
Ijust want to send this
cosmic question out into the void.

351
00:21:01,937 --> 00:21:03,234
So...

352
00:21:03,506 --> 00:21:05,770
...good night, dear void.

353
00:21:15,384 --> 00:21:16,942
I know you!

354
00:21:18,854 --> 00:21:19,821
I know you.

355
00:21:20,022 --> 00:21:21,853
Hello, Annabel, little girl.

356
00:21:22,258 --> 00:21:23,282
How are you?

357
00:21:23,526 --> 00:21:24,754
And you.

358
00:21:25,027 --> 00:21:26,619
Matthew, how are you?

359
00:21:27,029 --> 00:21:28,018
Good.

360
00:21:28,230 --> 00:21:29,959
Ready to say hello to New Jersey?

361
00:21:30,199 --> 00:21:32,565
Hello, New Jersey!

362
00:21:34,537 --> 00:21:35,629
Don't I get a "hello"?

363
00:21:37,373 --> 00:21:38,362
Hello, Gillian.

364
00:21:39,141 --> 00:21:41,871
kiss me. I'm going to be
your wicked stepmother.

365
00:21:45,147 --> 00:21:46,079
There you go.

366
00:21:46,315 --> 00:21:47,873
Hello. And who is this?

367
00:21:48,818 --> 00:21:51,787
Nanny Maureen. I brought her in case
you couldn't handle the kids.

368
00:21:52,354 --> 00:21:53,981
Maureen's getting a divorce.

369
00:21:55,391 --> 00:21:56,449
I'm sorry to hear that.

370
00:21:56,992 --> 00:21:58,459
It's my own fault.

371
00:21:58,661 --> 00:22:01,425
Never marry a man who lies.

372
00:22:02,064 --> 00:22:04,589
That is so wise. Yes.
Annabel, remember that.

373
00:22:04,867 --> 00:22:06,494
She taught Matt how to
spell his name.

374
00:22:07,002 --> 00:22:08,060
Really?

375
00:22:08,270 --> 00:22:09,828
-Let's hear it.
-F-O-X.

376
00:22:10,072 --> 00:22:11,437
Excellent.

377
00:22:11,640 --> 00:22:15,041
Excellent. I've got this covered.
You can have the day off.

378
00:22:15,244 --> 00:22:18,839
And you must be late for something.
Volunteering, rolling bandages...

379
00:22:19,081 --> 00:22:20,480
...for Bosnian refugees.

380
00:22:20,683 --> 00:22:23,914
I am. I'm having
my eggs harvested.

381
00:22:25,454 --> 00:22:28,082
And getting those eggs harvested.
Don't worry about a thing.

382
00:22:28,290 --> 00:22:29,348
See you later.

383
00:22:30,259 --> 00:22:31,248
Bye, Mom.

384
00:22:31,460 --> 00:22:35,692
All right, you guys, are you ready
to go out on the boat?

385
00:22:36,999 --> 00:22:39,160
What happened to you?
What happened?

386
00:22:54,316 --> 00:22:56,375
Come on. You stink.
One more time.

387
00:22:56,619 --> 00:22:58,280
Here, you can do that one.

388
00:23:02,224 --> 00:23:03,782
What do we win?

389
00:23:15,804 --> 00:23:17,135
Look, look, look!

390
00:23:52,007 --> 00:23:54,669
-How are the fish?
-They're very well. Very happy.

391
00:23:54,877 --> 00:23:56,105
Are they?

392
00:23:56,345 --> 00:23:58,245
You guys want to go to a movie?

393
00:23:58,447 --> 00:24:00,108
There's nothing good playing.

394
00:24:00,349 --> 00:24:02,544
Look, the storybook lady.

395
00:24:03,185 --> 00:24:06,245
Are we at the right time?
Yeah, let's go.

396
00:24:06,522 --> 00:24:08,547
"That it was I and I alone...

397
00:24:09,391 --> 00:24:12,883
...who had the idea for the great
and daring mouse plot.

398
00:24:13,095 --> 00:24:15,359
We all have our moments
of brilliance and glory...

399
00:24:15,564 --> 00:24:17,862
...and this was mine.

400
00:24:18,067 --> 00:24:19,125
'Why don't we,' I said...

401
00:24:19,335 --> 00:24:23,135
...'slip it into one of
Mrs. Pratchett's jars of sweets?

402
00:24:23,472 --> 00:24:24,461
And then...

403
00:24:24,707 --> 00:24:27,369
...when she puts her dirty hand in
to grab a handful...

404
00:24:27,576 --> 00:24:32,104
...she will grab a stinky,
dead mouse instead.'

405
00:24:32,314 --> 00:24:34,612
The other four stared at me in wonder.

406
00:24:34,817 --> 00:24:38,913
Then, as the sheer genius
of the plot began to sink in...

407
00:24:39,121 --> 00:24:41,248
...they all started grinning.

408
00:24:41,457 --> 00:24:43,789
They slapped me on the back.
They cheered me.

409
00:24:43,993 --> 00:24:45,460
They danced around the classroom.

410
00:24:45,661 --> 00:24:47,219
'We will do it today!' they cried.

411
00:24:47,429 --> 00:24:50,421
'We'll do it on the way home.
You had the idea,' they said to me.

412
00:24:50,632 --> 00:24:52,964
'So you can be the one who
puts the mouse in the jar.' "

413
00:24:56,572 --> 00:24:58,233
Who belongs to this fish?

414
00:24:58,440 --> 00:24:59,566
That's mine.

415
00:24:59,808 --> 00:25:02,242
Could you give me a hand
with these used books?

416
00:25:03,078 --> 00:25:04,909
And this is her best friend Tacy...

417
00:25:05,080 --> 00:25:06,479
...whose real name is Anastasia.

418
00:25:06,682 --> 00:25:09,947
And the next book, Betsy and Tacy
become friends with Tib...

419
00:25:10,152 --> 00:25:13,451
...whose real name, I am sorry
to tell you, is Thelma.

420
00:25:15,090 --> 00:25:17,854
The illustrations are hand-tipped.

421
00:25:18,527 --> 00:25:20,688
And that's why it costs so much?

422
00:25:21,096 --> 00:25:22,996
No, that's why it's worth so much.

423
00:25:23,198 --> 00:25:25,166
I want all of them.

424
00:25:25,367 --> 00:25:26,459
I'll think about it.

425
00:25:26,668 --> 00:25:28,431
That's a lot for your dad
to buy at one time.

426
00:25:28,704 --> 00:25:30,934
My dad gets me all the books I want.

427
00:25:31,140 --> 00:25:32,334
That's very nice of him.

428
00:25:33,242 --> 00:25:34,834
That's not my dad.
That's my nephew.

429
00:25:35,978 --> 00:25:39,470
I don't really think
that he could be your nephew.

430
00:25:39,948 --> 00:25:40,778
It's true.

431
00:25:40,983 --> 00:25:45,716
Annabel is my aunt.
Isn't that right, Aunt Annabel?

432
00:25:47,122 --> 00:25:47,952
And Matt is his--

433
00:25:48,157 --> 00:25:50,284
Wait, wait, let me guess.

434
00:25:50,492 --> 00:25:52,460
Are you his uncle?

435
00:25:52,661 --> 00:25:53,958
No.

436
00:25:54,129 --> 00:25:55,562
His grandfather?

437
00:25:57,132 --> 00:25:58,565
His great-grandfather?

438
00:25:58,867 --> 00:26:00,459
I'm his brother.

439
00:26:02,337 --> 00:26:04,202
Matt is my father's son.

440
00:26:04,406 --> 00:26:06,306
Annabel is my grandfather's daughter.

441
00:26:07,309 --> 00:26:08,833
We are...

442
00:26:09,645 --> 00:26:11,408
...an American family.

443
00:26:17,252 --> 00:26:18,184
Here you go, young lady.

444
00:26:18,387 --> 00:26:19,479
What's that?

445
00:26:19,822 --> 00:26:21,346
That's a handkerchief.

446
00:26:21,723 --> 00:26:23,816
Do children not even know
what handkerchiefs are?

447
00:26:24,026 --> 00:26:27,052
A handkerchief is a kleenex
you don't throw away. You see?

448
00:26:27,863 --> 00:26:29,660
My mother embroidered this for me.

449
00:26:29,832 --> 00:26:33,324
My initials and a daisy, because
daisies are my favorite flower.

450
00:26:34,336 --> 00:26:36,236
May I ask who you are?

451
00:26:36,872 --> 00:26:39,102
kathleen kelly. I own this store.

452
00:26:39,341 --> 00:26:40,273
And you are?

453
00:26:41,510 --> 00:26:43,501
Joe. Just call me Joe.

454
00:26:43,712 --> 00:26:45,077
We'll take these books.

455
00:26:47,249 --> 00:26:49,012
You're going to come back,
aren't you?

456
00:26:51,553 --> 00:26:52,542
Of course.

457
00:26:52,754 --> 00:26:53,584
See?

458
00:26:53,789 --> 00:26:55,279
That is why we won't go under.

459
00:26:55,524 --> 00:26:56,684
Our customers are loyal.

460
00:26:56,859 --> 00:26:58,952
They're opening a Fox Books
around the corner.

461
00:26:59,194 --> 00:27:00,126
Fox Books!

462
00:27:00,329 --> 00:27:02,297
-My daddy--
-Likes to buy discount.

463
00:27:02,531 --> 00:27:04,465
Don't tell anybody.
It's nothing to be proud of.

464
00:27:05,033 --> 00:27:06,694
F-O-X.

465
00:27:06,969 --> 00:27:09,369
That's amazing. You can spell fox.

466
00:27:10,372 --> 00:27:12,465
Can you spell dog?

467
00:27:12,774 --> 00:27:13,866
F-O-X.

468
00:27:14,042 --> 00:27:16,704
Look at this dinosaur book.
It's a pop-up dinosaur book.

469
00:27:16,979 --> 00:27:19,470
Wouldn't you like to have
a dinosaur book like that?

470
00:27:19,648 --> 00:27:22,116
Wouldn't you like to read that?

471
00:27:22,384 --> 00:27:25,717
Sit here and read Matt the book
until I take care of things.

472
00:27:25,921 --> 00:27:30,381
Whatever you do, just don't listen
to anything I say. Thank you.

473
00:27:31,093 --> 00:27:33,561
We'll take that pop-up book as well.
The dinosaur one.

474
00:27:33,729 --> 00:27:35,822
The world is not driven
by discounts, believe me.

475
00:27:36,064 --> 00:27:37,827
I have been in business forever.

476
00:27:38,066 --> 00:27:40,864
I started helping my mother
after school here when I was six...

477
00:27:41,069 --> 00:27:42,229
...and I used to watch her.

478
00:27:42,804 --> 00:27:45,466
It wasn't that she was just selling
books. It was that she was...

479
00:27:45,674 --> 00:27:48,666
...helping people become whoever
they were going to turn out to be.

480
00:27:48,911 --> 00:27:51,345
When you read a book as a child,
it becomes part of your identity...

481
00:27:51,547 --> 00:27:54,277
...in a way that no other reading
in your whole life does.

482
00:27:54,483 --> 00:27:56,417
And I have gotten carried away.

483
00:27:59,588 --> 00:28:01,249
Yeah, you have.

484
00:28:01,657 --> 00:28:03,784
You've made me feel....

485
00:28:06,628 --> 00:28:09,426
Enchanting.
Your mother was enchanting.

486
00:28:09,598 --> 00:28:10,690
Yes, she was.

487
00:28:11,133 --> 00:28:12,430
How will you pay for this?

488
00:28:13,101 --> 00:28:13,999
Cash.

489
00:28:14,603 --> 00:28:15,831
How did you know that?

490
00:28:16,838 --> 00:28:17,998
From the photograph.

491
00:28:19,007 --> 00:28:21,271
That you in the photograph?
What are you doing?

492
00:28:21,643 --> 00:28:22,940
Twirling.

493
00:28:24,179 --> 00:28:26,340
My mother and I used to twirl.

494
00:28:26,548 --> 00:28:30,177
Anyway, she left the store to me,
and I'll leave it to my daughter.

495
00:28:30,385 --> 00:28:31,943
-$73, please.
-How much?

496
00:28:32,187 --> 00:28:33,176
$73.

497
00:28:36,458 --> 00:28:39,450
How old is your daughter now?

498
00:28:40,796 --> 00:28:42,457
I don't have a daughter.

499
00:28:42,798 --> 00:28:43,890
I'm not married.

500
00:28:44,132 --> 00:28:45,463
But eventually....

501
00:28:45,701 --> 00:28:49,034
So the big bad Fox Books
can just go to hell.

502
00:28:50,806 --> 00:28:51,864
Here you go.

503
00:28:52,140 --> 00:28:54,165
Thank you. We're ready?

504
00:28:55,711 --> 00:28:57,338
This is nice.

505
00:28:57,980 --> 00:29:01,040
Goodbye, Annabel.
Goodbye, Matt.

506
00:29:04,853 --> 00:29:07,651
Matt, you know what?
I have to ask you another thing.

507
00:29:07,823 --> 00:29:09,313
Can you spell cat?

508
00:29:09,558 --> 00:29:11,355
F-O-X.

509
00:29:11,560 --> 00:29:12,891
F-O-X.

510
00:29:13,829 --> 00:29:16,059
Cat. Thanks.

511
00:29:19,067 --> 00:29:20,329
Good thing it wasn't the fish.

512
00:29:22,671 --> 00:29:24,161
Take care!

513
00:30:11,286 --> 00:30:14,050
No protests. No demonstrations.

514
00:30:14,222 --> 00:30:15,780
The neighborhood loves us.

515
00:30:16,058 --> 00:30:18,151
They're wondering where
we've been all these years.

516
00:30:18,393 --> 00:30:19,883
Wondering how they did without us.

517
00:30:20,062 --> 00:30:21,120
It's a hit!

518
00:30:21,330 --> 00:30:23,059
How's the children's department?

519
00:30:23,231 --> 00:30:25,096
It's early yet. School's not out.

520
00:30:25,300 --> 00:30:28,463
And there is that children's store
nearby. Shop Around The Corner.

521
00:30:28,737 --> 00:30:31,262
Cecilia's store. Cecilia kelly.

522
00:30:31,473 --> 00:30:33,304
I think we might have had
a date once.

523
00:30:33,508 --> 00:30:34,805
Her daughter owns it now.

524
00:30:35,010 --> 00:30:36,068
We'll crush it!

525
00:30:36,278 --> 00:30:38,007
She was enchanting.

526
00:30:43,919 --> 00:30:46,012
They've been open 6 days.
And we did...

527
00:30:46,254 --> 00:30:48,654
...$ 1 200 less than the same week...

528
00:30:49,358 --> 00:30:50,791
...last year.

529
00:30:50,992 --> 00:30:52,482
That could be a fluke, right?

530
00:30:53,495 --> 00:30:54,484
Or not.

531
00:30:55,664 --> 00:30:58,497
Listen, their store is new.
It's a novelty.

532
00:30:58,767 --> 00:31:01,930
It'll all shake out. Meanwhile,
I'm putting up more twinkle lights.

533
00:31:02,471 --> 00:31:03,995
That's a fine idea.

534
00:31:04,272 --> 00:31:06,263
What if we have to fold?

535
00:31:06,441 --> 00:31:08,807
I'm never going to find
another part-time job.

536
00:31:09,010 --> 00:31:12,446
Then I won't be able to pay
my rent, and I'll have to move.

537
00:31:12,614 --> 00:31:13,979
To Brooklyn.

538
00:31:14,182 --> 00:31:17,117
The joy of rent control.
Six rooms...

539
00:31:17,319 --> 00:31:18,786
...$450 a month.

540
00:31:19,020 --> 00:31:21,113
We know. You've told us
a million times.

541
00:31:21,289 --> 00:31:24,781
I can't believe you're bringing
this up at a time like this.

542
00:31:24,960 --> 00:31:28,361
It's like those people who brag
because they're tall.

543
00:31:28,630 --> 00:31:30,461
Guys, we are not going to fold.

544
00:31:33,568 --> 00:31:35,058
This place is a tomb.

545
00:31:35,270 --> 00:31:37,636
I'm going to the nut shop,
where's it's fun.

546
00:31:50,719 --> 00:31:51,549
Miranda!

547
00:31:55,323 --> 00:31:58,190
kathleen, are you surviving?

548
00:31:58,493 --> 00:32:02,156
We're excited about your new book.
When should we schedule a signing?

549
00:32:02,664 --> 00:32:04,154
It's being published in January.

550
00:32:05,100 --> 00:32:06,658
Will you be in business in January?

551
00:32:06,902 --> 00:32:08,096
I'm so worried.

552
00:32:08,336 --> 00:32:09,633
We're doing great.

553
00:32:09,838 --> 00:32:11,032
Aren't we?

554
00:32:11,239 --> 00:32:13,104
No difference whatsoever!

555
00:32:13,341 --> 00:32:14,399
Great.

556
00:32:14,676 --> 00:32:15,836
Thank God.

557
00:32:16,511 --> 00:32:18,172
You can count on me for anything.

558
00:32:18,747 --> 00:32:20,681
Support. Rallies. Picket lines.

559
00:32:20,849 --> 00:32:22,942
We can get the Times
to write something.

560
00:32:23,852 --> 00:32:25,376
Or that nut from the Observer.

561
00:32:27,355 --> 00:32:28,686
What nut in the Observer ?

562
00:32:28,890 --> 00:32:30,255
Frank something-or-other.

563
00:32:30,525 --> 00:32:32,516
The one who's so in love
with his typewriter.

564
00:32:32,761 --> 00:32:35,229
This is just the sort of thing
that would outrage him.

565
00:32:37,866 --> 00:32:39,629
A nut? She called me a nut?

566
00:32:40,135 --> 00:32:42,797
That's not the point.
She thinks my store is in trouble.

567
00:32:43,038 --> 00:32:45,598
Why would she say that?
There's enough business for us all.

568
00:32:45,807 --> 00:32:47,365
Yes, there is. No question.

569
00:32:47,576 --> 00:32:48,600
We are fine.

570
00:32:48,810 --> 00:32:50,801
You're more than fine.
You're absolutely fine.

571
00:32:51,046 --> 00:32:52,411
We are fine.

572
00:32:52,647 --> 00:32:54,046
How are you?

573
00:32:54,249 --> 00:32:55,307
Fine.

574
00:32:55,650 --> 00:32:58,084
Come in. Vince will be
so happy to see you.

575
00:32:58,386 --> 00:33:01,822
Congratulations. Guess who I
saw on the subway today?

576
00:33:02,057 --> 00:33:03,183
William Spungeon.

577
00:33:03,391 --> 00:33:04,653
I don't know him.

578
00:33:06,962 --> 00:33:09,021
This is amazing.
He said:

579
00:33:09,331 --> 00:33:11,458
"You should go to a retreat.

580
00:33:11,666 --> 00:33:14,294
You really should go to a retreat."

581
00:33:18,173 --> 00:33:20,232
Honey, will you get me
another drink? I'm out.

582
00:33:20,408 --> 00:33:22,000
"Because it's a
really great place...

583
00:33:22,744 --> 00:33:25,076
...to calm down."

584
00:33:25,313 --> 00:33:27,178
He said that to me.
Isn't that hilarious?

585
00:33:32,354 --> 00:33:33,912
Champagne, please.

586
00:33:34,656 --> 00:33:38,251
Stoli on the rocks.
But a fresh glass, please.

587
00:33:38,693 --> 00:33:40,183
White wine, please.

588
00:33:40,495 --> 00:33:41,826
Here you go.

589
00:33:51,973 --> 00:33:53,304
Remember me from the bookstore?

590
00:33:53,508 --> 00:33:55,703
Of course I remember you.

591
00:33:56,244 --> 00:33:57,711
How's your aunt?

592
00:33:58,480 --> 00:33:59,777
She's great. Thanks.

593
00:33:59,981 --> 00:34:01,471
I'd better go deliver this.

594
00:34:01,716 --> 00:34:04,344
I have a very thirsty date.
She's part camel.

595
00:34:04,553 --> 00:34:06,544
Joe, right? Joe, isn't it?

596
00:34:07,455 --> 00:34:08,717
And you are kathleen.

597
00:34:14,496 --> 00:34:15,622
kathleen kelly.

598
00:34:15,797 --> 00:34:17,321
Two white wine, please.

599
00:34:22,470 --> 00:34:26,463
I cannot believe that you were
speaking to Joe Fox.

600
00:34:26,808 --> 00:34:28,400
Joe Fox?

601
00:34:29,477 --> 00:34:30,136
As in--

602
00:34:30,312 --> 00:34:33,406
As in, he's going to
take over everything.

603
00:34:41,523 --> 00:34:43,650
Fox? Your last name is Fox.

604
00:34:44,826 --> 00:34:46,418
F-O-X.

605
00:34:47,696 --> 00:34:48,754
God...

606
00:34:48,964 --> 00:34:50,226
...l didn't realize--

607
00:34:50,432 --> 00:34:52,195
I didn't know--

608
00:34:52,834 --> 00:34:55,769
Who you were with?
I didn't know who you were with.

609
00:34:55,937 --> 00:34:57,495
Excuse me?

610
00:34:58,173 --> 00:35:00,107
It's from The Godfather.

611
00:35:00,442 --> 00:35:02,103
Sorry, it's from The Godfather.

612
00:35:02,344 --> 00:35:03,606
It's when...

613
00:35:03,845 --> 00:35:05,745
...the movie producer realizes
that Tom Hagen...

614
00:35:05,947 --> 00:35:08,507
...is an emissary of Vito Corleone.

615
00:35:08,717 --> 00:35:10,685
Just before the horse's head
ends up in the bed...

616
00:35:10,885 --> 00:35:13,445
...with all the bloody sheets.
Wakes up and it's--

617
00:35:17,792 --> 00:35:18,884
Never mind.

618
00:35:19,127 --> 00:35:21,220
You were spying on me, weren't you?

619
00:35:21,696 --> 00:35:23,186
You probably rented those children.

620
00:35:23,365 --> 00:35:24,389
Why would I spy on you?

621
00:35:24,633 --> 00:35:27,124
Because I am your competition,
which you know perfectly well...

622
00:35:27,369 --> 00:35:30,964
...or you wouldn't have put up the sign:
"Just around the corner."

623
00:35:31,740 --> 00:35:34,675
The entrance to our store
is around the corner.

624
00:35:34,876 --> 00:35:36,207
There's no other way to say it.

625
00:35:36,411 --> 00:35:39,539
It's not the name of our store.
It's where it is.

626
00:35:39,714 --> 00:35:40,976
And you do not own...

627
00:35:41,216 --> 00:35:43,377
...the phrase "around the corner."

628
00:35:46,388 --> 00:35:47,650
What is that?

629
00:35:48,056 --> 00:35:49,045
What are you doing?

630
00:35:49,658 --> 00:35:51,319
What is that? What are you doing?

631
00:35:51,660 --> 00:35:54,754
You're taking all the caviar?
That caviar is a garnish.

632
00:36:01,002 --> 00:36:01,832
Look...

633
00:36:02,070 --> 00:36:04,163
...the reason I came into
your store is because...

634
00:36:04,406 --> 00:36:06,499
...l was spending the day with
Annabel and Matt.

635
00:36:06,708 --> 00:36:08,039
I was buying them presents.

636
00:36:08,243 --> 00:36:10,040
I'm the type of guy
who buys his way...

637
00:36:10,245 --> 00:36:12,338
...into the hearts of children
who are relatives.

638
00:36:12,580 --> 00:36:16,175
There was only one place to find
a children's book in the neighborhood.

639
00:36:16,418 --> 00:36:17,612
That will not always be the case.

640
00:36:17,852 --> 00:36:19,581
And it was yours.
And it is...

641
00:36:19,921 --> 00:36:21,684
...a charming little bookstore.

642
00:36:21,923 --> 00:36:25,620
You probably sell, what,
$350,000 worth of books in a year?

643
00:36:25,860 --> 00:36:27,020
How did you know that?

644
00:36:27,262 --> 00:36:28,524
I'm in the book business.

645
00:36:29,531 --> 00:36:31,123
I am in the book business.

646
00:36:33,101 --> 00:36:34,090
I see.

647
00:36:34,803 --> 00:36:36,634
And we are the Price Club.

648
00:36:36,871 --> 00:36:40,329
Only instead of a ten-gallon vat
of olive oil for $3.99...

649
00:36:40,542 --> 00:36:44,342
...that won't even fit under your
kitchen cabinet, we sell cheap books.

650
00:36:44,546 --> 00:36:46,946
Me, a spy? Absolutely.

651
00:36:47,115 --> 00:36:48,946
I have in my possession...

652
00:36:49,217 --> 00:36:51,617
...the super-duper, secret printout
of the sales figures...

653
00:36:51,820 --> 00:36:54,812
...of a bookstore so inconsequential,
yet full of its own virtue...

654
00:36:55,056 --> 00:36:56,785
...that I was compelled
to rush over...

655
00:36:56,958 --> 00:36:58,823
...for fear that it will
put me out of business.

656
00:37:01,830 --> 00:37:03,320
What? What?

657
00:37:03,898 --> 00:37:05,559
How you doing? Frank Navasky.

658
00:37:06,835 --> 00:37:07,699
Joe Fox.

659
00:37:11,740 --> 00:37:14,004
The inventor of the superstore,
of course.

660
00:37:14,242 --> 00:37:16,142
The enemy of the mid-list novel.

661
00:37:16,344 --> 00:37:17,675
The destroyer of City Books.

662
00:37:17,912 --> 00:37:19,743
Tell me something.
How do you sleep at night?

663
00:37:20,749 --> 00:37:21,909
I use a wonderful...

664
00:37:22,150 --> 00:37:23,742
...over-the-counter drug.

665
00:37:23,985 --> 00:37:24,917
"Ultra-dorm."

666
00:37:25,487 --> 00:37:27,148
Don't take the whole thing.
Just half.

667
00:37:27,355 --> 00:37:29,414
You'll wake up without
even the tiniest hangover.

668
00:37:30,158 --> 00:37:31,853
You're Frank Navasky, aren't you?

669
00:37:32,093 --> 00:37:34,323
Your last piece in the Observer...

670
00:37:34,529 --> 00:37:37,089
...about Anthony Powell was brilliant.

671
00:37:38,266 --> 00:37:39,426
Brilliant. Yes.

672
00:37:40,335 --> 00:37:41,859
I'm Patricia Eden.

673
00:37:42,103 --> 00:37:43,661
Eden Books.

674
00:37:43,872 --> 00:37:47,035
This man is the greatest
living expert...

675
00:37:47,275 --> 00:37:48,765
...on Julius and Ethel Rosenberg.

676
00:37:49,010 --> 00:37:49,942
You really liked--

677
00:37:50,178 --> 00:37:52,043
This is kathleen kelly.

678
00:37:52,280 --> 00:37:55,681
My piece? I'm sorry. I just--
You know? I'm flattered.

679
00:37:55,884 --> 00:37:58,182
You write these things.
You think somebody'll mention them.

680
00:37:58,386 --> 00:38:00,513
The phone doesn't ring for a week
and you think:

681
00:38:00,855 --> 00:38:03,380
"I'm a fraud.
I'm a failure or something."

682
00:38:03,591 --> 00:38:04,853
You know what fascinated me...

683
00:38:05,059 --> 00:38:06,526
...about Julius and Ethel Rosenberg?

684
00:38:06,728 --> 00:38:09,026
Is how old they looked
when they were really just...

685
00:38:09,230 --> 00:38:10,060
...our age.

686
00:38:11,699 --> 00:38:12,631
You know?

687
00:38:13,468 --> 00:38:15,129
I'm so happy to have
finally met you.

688
00:38:16,771 --> 00:38:19,365
We'll talk. Have you ever
thought about doing a book?

689
00:38:19,574 --> 00:38:21,542
It's crossed my mind,
something relevant for today...

690
00:38:21,743 --> 00:38:24,712
...like the Luddite movement in
1 9th century England. We should talk.

691
00:38:24,913 --> 00:38:25,811
Call me.

692
00:38:26,047 --> 00:38:28,709
Have you ever had a caviar garnish?

693
00:38:34,622 --> 00:38:37,785
I had no idea Frank Navasky...

694
00:38:37,992 --> 00:38:40,517
...was going to be so down-to-earth.

695
00:38:41,229 --> 00:38:42,890
You know, you read his stuff...

696
00:38:43,131 --> 00:38:45,827
...you think he's going to be
so obscure and abstruse.

697
00:38:46,034 --> 00:38:48,969
He's always talking
about Heidegger...

698
00:38:49,170 --> 00:38:50,535
...and Foucault.

699
00:38:50,738 --> 00:38:54,003
And I have no idea what
any of it's about really.

700
00:38:59,314 --> 00:39:00,212
Where you going?

701
00:39:00,815 --> 00:39:02,908
I'm not tired. I'm not.

702
00:39:18,366 --> 00:39:22,166
Do you ever feel you've become
the worst version of yourself?

703
00:39:26,374 --> 00:39:28,035
That a Pandora's box...

704
00:39:28,243 --> 00:39:32,680
...of all the secret, hateful parts,
your arrogance, your spite...

705
00:39:32,881 --> 00:39:34,280
...your condescension...

706
00:39:34,515 --> 00:39:36,039
...has sprung open?

707
00:39:36,251 --> 00:39:39,049
Someone provokes you,
and instead ofjust smiling...

708
00:39:39,287 --> 00:39:42,188
...and moving on, you zing them?

709
00:39:42,390 --> 00:39:44,915
"Hello, it's Mr. Nasty. "

710
00:39:45,760 --> 00:39:48,593
I'm sure you have no idea
what I'm talking about.

711
00:39:49,631 --> 00:39:52,862
No, I know what you mean,
and I'm completelyjealous.

712
00:39:55,036 --> 00:39:57,630
What happens to me when I'm provoked
is I get tongue-tied.

713
00:39:57,872 --> 00:39:59,464
My mind goes...

714
00:39:59,974 --> 00:40:00,963
...blank.

715
00:40:04,045 --> 00:40:06,309
Then I toss and turn all night...

716
00:40:06,547 --> 00:40:08,913
...trying to figure out
what I should have said.

717
00:40:12,687 --> 00:40:14,552
What should I have said,
for example, to the...

718
00:40:14,756 --> 00:40:17,316
...bottom-dweller...

719
00:40:21,362 --> 00:40:23,830
...who recently belittled
my existence?

720
00:40:32,941 --> 00:40:34,033
Nothing.

721
00:40:35,009 --> 00:40:36,476
Nothing. Even now.

722
00:40:36,678 --> 00:40:37,770
Even now...

723
00:40:38,012 --> 00:40:38,910
...days later...

724
00:40:39,113 --> 00:40:40,512
...l can't figure it out.

725
00:40:41,049 --> 00:40:44,917
Wouldn't it be wonderful if I could
pass all my zingers to you?

726
00:40:45,119 --> 00:40:48,919
Then I'd never behave badly and
you could behave badly all the time.

727
00:40:49,123 --> 00:40:50,283
And we'd both be happy.

728
00:40:50,491 --> 00:40:52,049
On the other hand,
I must warn you...

729
00:40:52,260 --> 00:40:55,559
...that when you finally say
the thing you mean to say...

730
00:40:55,763 --> 00:40:59,893
...the moment you mean to say it,
remorse inevitably follows.

731
00:41:05,139 --> 00:41:07,573
Do you think we should meet?

732
00:41:17,986 --> 00:41:19,385
Meet?

733
00:41:19,954 --> 00:41:21,717
Oh, my God.

734
00:42:23,885 --> 00:42:25,819
$72.27.

735
00:42:27,789 --> 00:42:30,121
This is a cash-only line.

736
00:42:32,493 --> 00:42:33,517
Cash only.

737
00:42:34,128 --> 00:42:35,561
Oh, my God.

738
00:42:36,464 --> 00:42:38,056
I just have a credit card.

739
00:42:38,299 --> 00:42:39,459
I'm sorry. Is that okay?

740
00:42:39,667 --> 00:42:41,225
No, it's not okay.

741
00:42:41,636 --> 00:42:42,796
There's a sign.

742
00:42:44,005 --> 00:42:45,870
I'm sorry. I'm very sorry.

743
00:42:46,074 --> 00:42:49,771
I never do this. But I ask you to make
an exception in this one case.

744
00:42:49,977 --> 00:42:51,638
You have no cash?

745
00:42:51,846 --> 00:42:52,744
She has no cash.

746
00:42:52,980 --> 00:42:53,844
No, she has no cash.

747
00:42:54,048 --> 00:42:55,413
Get on another line, lady.

748
00:42:55,616 --> 00:42:57,049
I have a dollar. That's all I have.

749
00:42:57,251 --> 00:42:59,014
I have a dollar. One dollar.

750
00:42:59,220 --> 00:43:01,211
Is there anything you can do?

751
00:43:02,890 --> 00:43:03,857
Do you need some money?

752
00:43:04,058 --> 00:43:05,889
No, I do not need any money.

753
00:43:06,094 --> 00:43:06,924
Thank you very much.

754
00:43:07,161 --> 00:43:09,026
Get in another line.

755
00:43:09,664 --> 00:43:10,961
Rose.

756
00:43:11,165 --> 00:43:13,258
That is a great name. Rose.

757
00:43:13,568 --> 00:43:14,500
This is kathleen.

758
00:43:14,702 --> 00:43:15,532
I'm Joe. And--

759
00:43:15,736 --> 00:43:16,794
And I'm Henry.

760
00:43:17,004 --> 00:43:18,938
Henry, how are you? Happy holidays.

761
00:43:19,173 --> 00:43:21,368
This is a credit card machine.

762
00:43:22,076 --> 00:43:23,065
Happy Thanksgiving.

763
00:43:24,579 --> 00:43:26,513
It's your turn to say
"Happy Thanksgiving" back.

764
00:43:27,415 --> 00:43:29,178
Happy Thanksgiving back.

765
00:43:29,550 --> 00:43:30,574
knock, knock.

766
00:43:31,552 --> 00:43:32,519
Who's there?

767
00:43:33,087 --> 00:43:33,917
Orange.

768
00:43:34,689 --> 00:43:35,747
Orange who?

769
00:43:35,957 --> 00:43:37,424
Orange you going to give us a break...

770
00:43:37,625 --> 00:43:41,083
...by zipping this credit card
through the credit card machine?

771
00:43:41,863 --> 00:43:43,194
Come on. You can do it.

772
00:43:43,397 --> 00:43:44,193
Zip, zip.

773
00:43:45,066 --> 00:43:46,192
There you go.

774
00:43:47,268 --> 00:43:48,098
Rose?

775
00:43:50,138 --> 00:43:52,197
That is a great name.

776
00:43:52,940 --> 00:43:53,929
So you're fine.

777
00:43:55,076 --> 00:43:55,906
Fine.

778
00:43:56,110 --> 00:43:58,908
Happy Thanksgiving.
Henry, happy Thanksgiving.

779
00:43:59,947 --> 00:44:01,608
I'm so sorry.
Really, I apologize.

780
00:44:01,816 --> 00:44:04,284
-From the bottom of my heart.
-So sign already!

781
00:44:04,952 --> 00:44:06,112
I'd like to get home.

782
00:44:06,320 --> 00:44:08,880
You have my pen.

783
00:44:11,859 --> 00:44:15,192
The sun'll come out tomorrow

784
00:44:15,596 --> 00:44:17,564
Bet your bottom dollar that

785
00:44:17,765 --> 00:44:20,598
Tomorrow there'll be sun

786
00:44:22,036 --> 00:44:25,028
Just thinking about tomorrow

