1052
00:58:37,657 --> 00:58:39,818
I always take
a relationship to the next level.

1053
00:58:40,027 --> 00:58:43,622
If that works out, I take it
to the next level after that.

1054
00:58:43,830 --> 00:58:47,994
Till I finally reach that level where
it becomes absolutely necessary...

1055
00:58:48,201 --> 00:58:49,190
...for me to leave.

1056
00:58:51,371 --> 00:58:53,100
I'm not going to stay that long anyway.

1057
00:58:53,306 --> 00:58:54,364
I already said that, didn't l?

1058
00:59:00,147 --> 00:59:03,412
Well, okay. Caf Lalo.
This is it.

1059
00:59:04,518 --> 00:59:07,248
Eight o'clock.
Boy, we got here fast, didn't we?

1060
00:59:10,090 --> 00:59:13,218
This woman is the most adorable creature
I've ever been in contact with.

1061
00:59:13,493 --> 00:59:17,327
And if she turns out even to be
as good-looking as a mailbox...

1062
00:59:17,531 --> 00:59:21,331
...l'd be crazy not to turn my life
upside-down and marry her.

1063
00:59:22,102 --> 00:59:24,093
She could be a real dog.

1064
00:59:24,304 --> 00:59:25,430
But good luck.

1065
00:59:29,776 --> 00:59:31,869
Would you go and look for me?

1066
00:59:32,112 --> 00:59:35,138
Yes, go look through the window
and check her out. Please?

1067
00:59:35,348 --> 00:59:36,542
All right.

1068
00:59:38,885 --> 00:59:41,080
-You're pathetic, man.
-I know.

1069
00:59:43,290 --> 00:59:45,224
All right. I'll see what I see.

1070
00:59:45,959 --> 00:59:47,290
You see her?

1071
00:59:48,595 --> 00:59:49,619
Wait, yeah.

1072
00:59:49,963 --> 00:59:52,397
I see a very beautiful girl.

1073
00:59:52,866 --> 00:59:54,356
She's fine.

1074
00:59:55,302 --> 00:59:57,167
-I knew it.
-She's gorgeous.

1075
00:59:57,370 --> 00:59:58,860
I knew she would be.
I knew it.

1076
00:59:59,072 --> 01:00:00,539
But no book.

1077
01:00:03,877 --> 01:00:04,844
All right.

1078
01:00:05,045 --> 01:00:07,104
Okay, wait. Wait a minute.

1079
01:00:07,314 --> 01:00:10,511
There's a book with a flower.
So this got to be her.

1080
01:00:10,717 --> 01:00:12,207
And what does she look like?

1081
01:00:12,786 --> 01:00:14,083
Can't see her. Waiter's blocking.

1082
01:00:14,321 --> 01:00:15,583
Damn it!

1083
01:00:15,822 --> 01:00:16,880
Hold on. He's moving.

1084
01:00:20,127 --> 01:00:21,219
Can you see her?

1085
01:00:23,130 --> 01:00:23,960
Can you see her?

1086
01:00:25,899 --> 01:00:27,093
Yeah.

1087
01:00:27,300 --> 01:00:28,198
And?

1088
01:00:30,604 --> 01:00:32,265
She's very pretty.

1089
01:00:32,472 --> 01:00:33,871
She is!

1090
01:00:34,074 --> 01:00:36,474
I knew she would be!
She had to be!

1091
01:00:36,710 --> 01:00:38,610
She had to be!

1092
01:00:40,580 --> 01:00:41,672
You know what?

1093
01:00:41,882 --> 01:00:43,315
She look--

1094
01:00:44,384 --> 01:00:47,945
I mean, she almost has
the same coloring as...

1095
01:00:48,155 --> 01:00:49,622
...that kathleen kelly person.

1096
01:00:49,823 --> 01:00:51,222
kathleen kelly
of the little bookstore?

1097
01:00:51,424 --> 01:00:53,051
Why not? You said you thought
she was attractive.

1098
01:00:53,260 --> 01:00:56,559
Absolutely, yes. Why not?
Who cares about kathleen kelly?

1099
01:00:56,763 --> 01:01:00,096
Well, if you don't like
kathleen kelly...

1100
01:01:00,400 --> 01:01:02,265
...l can tell you right now...

1101
01:01:03,069 --> 01:01:04,161
...you ain't going to like this girl.

1102
01:01:05,572 --> 01:01:06,402
Why not?

1103
01:01:08,241 --> 01:01:10,141
Because it is kathleen kelly.

1104
01:01:23,256 --> 01:01:24,985
So what are you going to do?

1105
01:01:28,762 --> 01:01:30,286
Nothing.

1106
01:01:30,797 --> 01:01:32,890
You're going
to let her wait all night?

1107
01:01:33,099 --> 01:01:35,260
Yes. That's exactly
what I'm going to do.

1108
01:01:36,603 --> 01:01:39,003
Good night, kevin.
I'll see you in the morning.

1109
01:01:48,114 --> 01:01:49,581
Do you mind if I borrow this chair?

1110
01:01:49,783 --> 01:01:51,614
Yes, I mind. Sorry.

1111
01:01:51,818 --> 01:01:53,683
I'm expecting someone.

1112
01:02:07,467 --> 01:02:09,367
Would you like another tea?

1113
01:02:09,970 --> 01:02:11,631
Yes. Thank you.

1114
01:02:47,274 --> 01:02:50,175
This is a coincidence.
Would you mind if I sat down?

1115
01:02:50,377 --> 01:02:53,505
Yes, I would, actually.
I'm expecting someone.

1116
01:02:54,581 --> 01:02:55,570
Pride and Prejudice.

1117
01:02:56,583 --> 01:02:57,515
Do you mind?

1118
01:02:57,784 --> 01:02:59,251
I bet you read that book every year.

1119
01:02:59,452 --> 01:03:00,919
I bet you just love that...

1120
01:03:01,121 --> 01:03:02,782
...Mr. Darcy.

1121
01:03:03,023 --> 01:03:06,117
Your sentimental heart beats wildly
at the thought he and...

1122
01:03:06,359 --> 01:03:08,020
...you know, whatever her name is...

1123
01:03:08,228 --> 01:03:11,197
...are truly, honestly going
to end up together.

1124
01:03:14,968 --> 01:03:15,866
Can I get you something?

1125
01:03:16,069 --> 01:03:17,195
No. He's not staying.

1126
01:03:17,404 --> 01:03:18,371
Mochaccino decaf, nonfat.

1127
01:03:19,105 --> 01:03:20,265
No. You are not staying!

1128
01:03:21,408 --> 01:03:22,534
I'll stay until your friend gets here.

1129
01:03:24,911 --> 01:03:25,969
Is he late?

1130
01:03:26,446 --> 01:03:29,506
The heroine of Pride and Prejudice
is Elizabeth Bennet.

1131
01:03:29,716 --> 01:03:33,277
She is a great and complex character.
Not that you would know.

1132
01:03:33,486 --> 01:03:35,351
As a matter of fact, I've read it.

1133
01:03:35,555 --> 01:03:36,783
Good for you.

1134
01:03:37,557 --> 01:03:39,718
I think you'd discover a lot of things
if you really knew me.

1135
01:03:40,327 --> 01:03:42,022
If I really knew you,
I know what I'd find.

1136
01:03:42,228 --> 01:03:44,128
Instead of a brain, a cash register.

1137
01:03:44,331 --> 01:03:46,060
Instead of a heart, a bottom line.

1138
01:03:50,170 --> 01:03:51,000
What?

1139
01:03:51,237 --> 01:03:52,397
I just had a breakthrough.

1140
01:03:52,605 --> 01:03:53,469
What is it?

1141
01:03:53,673 --> 01:03:55,766
I have you to thank for it.
For the first time in my life...

1142
01:03:55,975 --> 01:03:58,603
...when confronted with a horrible,
insensitive person...

1143
01:03:58,812 --> 01:04:01,337
...l knew exactly what I wanted
to say, and I said it.

1144
01:04:02,082 --> 01:04:03,242
You have a gift for it.

1145
01:04:03,450 --> 01:04:05,748
That was a perfect blend
of poetry and meanness.

1146
01:04:06,186 --> 01:04:07,915
Meanness? Let me tell
you something about meanness.

1147
01:04:08,121 --> 01:04:11,522
Don't misunderstand me.
I'm trying to pay you a compliment.

1148
01:04:12,459 --> 01:04:14,723
Why are you touching that?
What are you doing?

1149
01:04:14,928 --> 01:04:17,192
Is this a red rose? No.
It's a crimson rose.

1150
01:04:17,497 --> 01:04:18,964
Something you read in a book,
no doubt.

1151
01:04:19,165 --> 01:04:20,154
It's funny to you, isn't it?

1152
01:04:20,934 --> 01:04:22,799
Everything is a joke to you.

1153
01:04:32,645 --> 01:04:34,010
Please leave.

1154
01:04:34,214 --> 01:04:36,011
Please, please leave. I beg you.

1155
01:04:43,456 --> 01:04:44,650
Thank you.

1156
01:05:06,079 --> 01:05:09,412
You know what that hanky reminds
me of? First day I met you.

1157
01:05:09,649 --> 01:05:11,480
First day you lied to me.

1158
01:05:11,684 --> 01:05:13,515
-I didn't lie to you.
-You did too.

1159
01:05:13,720 --> 01:05:15,881
-No, I didn't. I did not.
-Yes, you did. Did too.

1160
01:05:17,824 --> 01:05:18,813
You did too.

1161
01:05:19,025 --> 01:05:22,188
I thought all that Fox stuff
was so charming. F-O-X.

1162
01:05:22,395 --> 01:05:23,828
Well, I didn't lie about it.

1163
01:05:25,098 --> 01:05:26,895
"Joe"? "Just call me Joe."

1164
01:05:27,100 --> 01:05:27,930
Sure.

1165
01:05:28,168 --> 01:05:31,137
As if you were a stupid
22-year-old girl with no last name.

1166
01:05:31,337 --> 01:05:33,430
"Hi, I'm kimberly." "Hi, I'm Janice."

1167
01:05:33,673 --> 01:05:35,732
Don't they know you're supposed
to have a last name?

1168
01:05:35,942 --> 01:05:38,308
It's like they're an entire generation
of cocktail waitresses.

1169
01:05:38,511 --> 01:05:39,500
Look.

1170
01:05:41,548 --> 01:05:44,039
I am not
a 22-year-old cocktail waitress.

1171
01:05:44,250 --> 01:05:45,148
That is not what I meant.

1172
01:05:45,351 --> 01:05:47,444
When I said the thing about
the cans of olive oil...

1173
01:05:47,687 --> 01:05:48,847
...that's not what I meant.

1174
01:05:49,189 --> 01:05:53,523
You poor, sad multimillionaire.
I feel so sorry for you.

1175
01:05:59,566 --> 01:06:01,363
Take a wild guess
that's not him either?

1176
01:06:03,703 --> 01:06:05,864
So who is he, I wonder?

1177
01:06:06,473 --> 01:06:09,203
Certainly not, I gather,
the world's greatest living expert...

1178
01:06:09,409 --> 01:06:11,468
...on Julius and Ethel Rosenberg.

1179
01:06:12,111 --> 01:06:14,477
But somebody else entirely different.

1180
01:06:15,248 --> 01:06:17,148
Will you be mean to him too?

1181
01:06:17,383 --> 01:06:18,816
No, I will not.

1182
01:06:19,252 --> 01:06:22,483
The man who is coming here
tonight is completely unlike you.

1183
01:06:22,755 --> 01:06:25,849
The man who is coming here
tonight is kind and funny.

1184
01:06:26,059 --> 01:06:28,323
He's got the most wonderful
sense of humor.

1185
01:06:28,561 --> 01:06:29,550
But...

1186
01:06:30,163 --> 01:06:31,721
...he's not here.

1187
01:06:32,632 --> 01:06:34,691
If he's not here, he has a reason...

1188
01:06:34,901 --> 01:06:38,234
...because there is not a cruel
or careless bone in his body.

1189
01:06:38,438 --> 01:06:40,702
I wouldn't expect you
to understand anybody like that.

1190
01:06:40,907 --> 01:06:43,705
You with your theme park, multilevel...

1191
01:06:43,910 --> 01:06:45,878
...homogenize-the-world mochaccinoland.

1192
01:06:46,079 --> 01:06:47,478
You've deluded
yourself into thinking...

1193
01:06:47,680 --> 01:06:50,581
...you're some sort of benefactor
bringing books to the masses.

1194
01:06:50,850 --> 01:06:53,512
But no one will ever remember you,
Joe Fox.

1195
01:06:53,753 --> 01:06:55,880
And maybe no one
will remember me either.

1196
01:06:56,089 --> 01:06:58,353
But plenty of people remember my mother.

1197
01:06:58,591 --> 01:06:59,888
And they think she was fine...

1198
01:07:00,093 --> 01:07:02,755
...and they think her store
was something special.

1199
01:07:04,163 --> 01:07:06,688
You are nothing but a suit.

1200
01:07:20,213 --> 01:07:21,805
That's my cue.

1201
01:07:25,451 --> 01:07:26,383
Good night.

1202
01:08:42,028 --> 01:08:46,158
So then the agent asks for
$600,000 and I said to her:

1203
01:08:46,366 --> 01:08:49,597
"If you think I'm even going
to talk to you...

1204
01:08:49,802 --> 01:08:51,736
...about paying that kind of
advance for an author...

1205
01:08:51,938 --> 01:08:56,671
...whose last book is being used
as trivets all over the whole world...

1206
01:08:56,876 --> 01:08:59,140
...you are completely crazy."

1207
01:08:59,545 --> 01:09:03,174
She was insulting and provocative.
The only thing pleasant about her...

1208
01:09:04,083 --> 01:09:06,984
...was the way her hair
fell across her forehead.

1209
01:09:07,220 --> 01:09:09,518
But underneath
that disagreeable exterior...

1210
01:09:09,722 --> 01:09:11,189
...she may turn out to be a real--

1211
01:09:11,391 --> 01:09:13,291
A real bitch.

1212
01:09:13,493 --> 01:09:14,653
Let's not talk about it.

1213
01:09:14,861 --> 01:09:17,523
I'm going back to the office.
I'm sure you have work.

1214
01:09:17,730 --> 01:09:18,788
Not really.

1215
01:09:18,998 --> 01:09:22,058
This place is a well-oiled
machine, my friend.

1216
01:09:23,970 --> 01:09:26,404
So? What happened?

1217
01:09:26,839 --> 01:09:28,306
He never came.

1218
01:09:28,508 --> 01:09:29,566
He stood you up.

1219
01:09:29,776 --> 01:09:33,405
I wouldn't characterize it that way.
I think something happened.

1220
01:09:33,613 --> 01:09:37,481
Something terrible and unexpected
that made it impossible for him to....

1221
01:09:38,117 --> 01:09:40,950
What if he showed up,
took one look at me and left?

1222
01:09:41,154 --> 01:09:43,179
Not possible.

1223
01:09:43,756 --> 01:09:46,816
Maybe there was a subway accident.

1224
01:09:47,026 --> 01:09:48,015
Absolutely.

1225
01:09:48,261 --> 01:09:50,695
A train got trapped underground
with him inside.

1226
01:09:50,930 --> 01:09:51,726
And no phone.

1227
01:09:51,931 --> 01:09:54,399
And you know how those
express trains create suction.

1228
01:09:54,600 --> 01:09:56,465
He got sucked onto the tracks.

1229
01:09:56,669 --> 01:09:57,693
The third rail.

1230
01:09:58,104 --> 01:09:59,696
He's toast.

1231
01:09:59,939 --> 01:10:00,871
What happened?

1232
01:10:02,108 --> 01:10:03,507
He was unable to make it.

1233
01:10:04,177 --> 01:10:05,508
He stood you up?

1234
01:10:08,614 --> 01:10:09,512
Maybe...

1235
01:10:10,183 --> 01:10:13,152
...he had a car accident.
Those cab drivers are maniacs.

1236
01:10:13,352 --> 01:10:17,516
They hit something and you slam
into that plastic partition.

1237
01:10:17,724 --> 01:10:21,091
Or his elbows could be in splints,
so he couldn't dial.

1238
01:10:21,294 --> 01:10:23,660
Or he could be unconscious.

1239
01:10:23,863 --> 01:10:24,852
In a coma.

1240
01:10:25,465 --> 01:10:27,296
Stuck in intensive care.

1241
01:10:27,567 --> 01:10:29,159
With that heart monitor beeping.

1242
01:10:29,368 --> 01:10:30,528
And, like....

1243
01:10:30,737 --> 01:10:31,795
No phone.

1244
01:10:40,246 --> 01:10:41,076
What are you saying?

1245
01:10:42,515 --> 01:10:43,482
It could be.

1246
01:10:43,883 --> 01:10:46,374
He was arrested
two blocks from the caf.

1247
01:10:46,586 --> 01:10:48,315
Is there a picture?

1248
01:10:51,524 --> 01:10:52,821
So that explains it.

1249
01:10:54,026 --> 01:10:54,890
He was in jail.

1250
01:10:56,529 --> 01:10:57,587
And there was a phone.

1251
01:10:57,830 --> 01:10:59,957
But he only got one call,
so he had to call his lawyer.

1252
01:11:00,166 --> 01:11:02,066
You are so lucky.

1253
01:11:02,502 --> 01:11:03,400
You could be dead.

1254
01:11:06,005 --> 01:11:08,803
He couldn't possibly
be the Rooftop killer!

1255
01:11:09,008 --> 01:11:12,273
Remember when you thought
Frank might be the Unabomber?

1256
01:11:12,512 --> 01:11:13,501
Well...

1257
01:11:14,180 --> 01:11:15,579
...that was different.

1258
01:11:16,349 --> 01:11:18,647
How long did you sit there all alone?

1259
01:11:18,851 --> 01:11:21,217
Not long. Joe Fox came in.

1260
01:11:22,455 --> 01:11:24,821
I don't want to talk about it.
Let's just get to work.

1261
01:11:25,024 --> 01:11:28,187
There's got to be something to do.
There's always something to do.

1262
01:11:29,428 --> 01:11:30,258
Look at this.

1263
01:11:30,463 --> 01:11:32,522
He looks kind of cute.

1264
01:11:34,634 --> 01:11:35,828
So?

1265
01:11:36,035 --> 01:11:38,868
He was unavoidably detained.

1266
01:11:39,205 --> 01:11:41,469
He stood you up?

1267
01:11:45,545 --> 01:11:47,740
I've been thinking about you.

1268
01:11:48,714 --> 01:11:51,945
Last night I went to meet you,
and you weren't there.

1269
01:11:53,719 --> 01:11:55,016
I wish I knew why.

1270
01:11:55,221 --> 01:11:57,553
I felt so foolish.

1271
01:11:59,392 --> 01:12:01,292
As I waited, someone else showed up.

1272
01:12:01,494 --> 01:12:04,793
A man who has made
my professional life a misery.

1273
01:12:04,997 --> 01:12:07,465
And an amazing thing happened.

1274
01:12:09,735 --> 01:12:11,600
I was able, for the first time...

1275
01:12:11,804 --> 01:12:13,931
...to say the exact thing
I wanted to say...

1276
01:12:14,140 --> 01:12:17,075
...at the exact moment
I wanted to say it.

1277
01:12:17,577 --> 01:12:21,343
And of course,
afterwards I felt terrible...

1278
01:12:21,747 --> 01:12:23,977
...just as you said I would.

1279
01:12:24,750 --> 01:12:26,012
I was cruel...

1280
01:12:26,219 --> 01:12:27,709
...and I'm never cruel.

1281
01:12:28,521 --> 01:12:31,547
Though I can hardly believe
what I said mattered to this man.

1282
01:12:31,757 --> 01:12:34,817
To him, I am just a bug to be crushed.

1283
01:12:35,595 --> 01:12:36,892
But what if it did?

1284
01:12:37,096 --> 01:12:38,996
No matter what he's done to me...

1285
01:12:39,198 --> 01:12:41,063
...there is no excuse for my behavior.

1286
01:12:41,834 --> 01:12:43,165
Anyway...

1287
01:12:43,402 --> 01:12:45,870
...l so wanted to talk to you.

1288
01:12:46,706 --> 01:12:49,174
I hope you have a good reason
for not being there last night.

1289
01:12:49,375 --> 01:12:53,106
You don't seem like the kind of
person who'd do something like that.

1290
01:12:53,779 --> 01:12:55,906
The odd thing about this
form of communication...

1291
01:12:56,115 --> 01:12:58,913
...is you're more likely to talk
about nothing than something.

1292
01:12:59,118 --> 01:13:00,779
But ljust want to say...

1293
01:13:01,020 --> 01:13:04,649
...that all this nothing has meant
more to me than so many...

1294
01:13:04,857 --> 01:13:06,518
...somethings.

1295
01:13:07,860 --> 01:13:09,623
So, thanks.

1296
01:13:25,878 --> 01:13:27,368
Goodbye.

1297
01:14:21,267 --> 01:14:22,996
I am in...

1298
01:14:26,439 --> 01:14:27,963
... Vancouver.

1299
01:14:37,683 --> 01:14:38,877
I was stuck in a meeting...

1300
01:14:39,118 --> 01:14:40,813
...which I couldn't get out of...

1301
01:14:41,020 --> 01:14:42,282
...and...

1302
01:14:42,655 --> 01:14:44,486
...the electricity went
out in the building.

1303
01:14:44,690 --> 01:14:46,021
And...

1304
01:14:46,225 --> 01:14:47,590
...we were trapped...

1305
01:14:47,793 --> 01:14:51,422
...on the 38th floor, and...

1306
01:14:51,630 --> 01:14:54,190
...the telephone system blew too...

1307
01:15:01,140 --> 01:15:03,199
...amazingly enough.

1308
01:15:38,344 --> 01:15:39,777
Dear friend.

1309
01:15:43,015 --> 01:15:46,007
I cannot tell you
what happened last night.

1310
01:15:47,253 --> 01:15:49,346
But I beg you
from the bottom of my heart...

1311
01:15:49,555 --> 01:15:51,716
...to forgive me for not being there.

1312
01:16:00,499 --> 01:16:02,091
For what happened.

1313
01:16:04,537 --> 01:16:08,268
I feel terrible that you
found yourself in a situation...

1314
01:16:08,474 --> 01:16:11,375
...that caused you additional pain.

1315
01:16:13,612 --> 01:16:15,580
But I'm absolutely sure...

1316
01:16:15,915 --> 01:16:19,476
...that whatever you said
last night was provoked.

1317
01:16:19,718 --> 01:16:21,379
Even deserved.

1318
01:16:24,890 --> 01:16:29,122
Everyone says things they regret
when they're worried or stressed.

1319
01:16:31,163 --> 01:16:33,996
You were expecting to see
someone you trusted...

1320
01:16:34,733 --> 01:16:37,167
...and met the enemy instead.

1321
01:16:40,639 --> 01:16:42,664
The fault is mine.

1322
01:16:45,911 --> 01:16:47,845
Someday I'll explain everything.

1323
01:16:48,247 --> 01:16:49,509
Meanwhile...

1324
01:16:49,748 --> 01:16:51,238
...l'm still here.

1325
01:16:52,184 --> 01:16:53,014
Talk to me.

1326
01:16:53,252 --> 01:16:56,278
Did he say anything about
wanting to meet you again?

1327
01:16:56,489 --> 01:16:58,650
No, not really.

1328
01:16:58,858 --> 01:17:00,189
Listen, it doesn't matter.

1329
01:17:00,426 --> 01:17:03,156
We'll be like George Bernard Shaw
and Mrs. Patrick Campbell.

1330
01:17:03,362 --> 01:17:04,761
We'll write letters our whole lives.

1331
01:17:06,465 --> 01:17:09,263
Thank you for the scones.
They look lovely.

1332
01:17:09,468 --> 01:17:12,767
Birdie, where was this one taken?

1333
01:17:13,205 --> 01:17:14,172
Seville.

1334
01:17:14,373 --> 01:17:16,432
When you fell madly in love?

1335
01:17:17,476 --> 01:17:20,502
So, dearie,
what have you decided to do?

1336
01:17:20,779 --> 01:17:23,270
Close. We're going to close.

1337
01:17:24,183 --> 01:17:25,115
Close.

1338
01:17:25,718 --> 01:17:27,185
Closing the store...

1339
01:17:27,386 --> 01:17:29,854
...is the brave thing to do.

1340
01:17:30,856 --> 01:17:32,585
You are such a liar.

1341
01:17:32,791 --> 01:17:33,621
But thank you.

1342
01:17:34,793 --> 01:17:38,957
You are daring to imagine that you
could have a different life.

1343
01:17:40,799 --> 01:17:44,291
I know it doesn't feel like that.
You feel like a big fat failure now.

1344
01:17:45,971 --> 01:17:47,131
But you're not.

1345
01:17:47,473 --> 01:17:51,637
You are marching into the unknown,
armed with...

1346
01:17:51,844 --> 01:17:52,811
...nothing.

1347
01:17:53,546 --> 01:17:55,138
Have a sandwich.

1348
01:17:56,248 --> 01:17:57,306
Well, not nothing.

1349
01:17:57,683 --> 01:17:59,674
I have a little money saved.

1350
01:17:59,885 --> 01:18:03,150
If you need more, ask me.
I'm very rich.

1351
01:18:03,355 --> 01:18:06,813
I bought lntel at six.

1352
01:18:10,129 --> 01:18:11,323
I suppose you want me...

1353
01:18:11,530 --> 01:18:12,929
...to tell you who it was...

1354
01:18:13,165 --> 01:18:15,497
...l fell madly in love with.

1355
01:18:16,402 --> 01:18:17,664
But I'm not going to tell.

1356
01:18:18,337 --> 01:18:19,827
Who was it?

1357
01:18:20,706 --> 01:18:23,766
Come on, tell. That's so mean.

1358
01:18:24,944 --> 01:18:26,138
But so romantic.

1359
01:18:26,345 --> 01:18:28,836
-It wasn't meant to be.
-Why not?

1360
01:18:29,900 --> 01:18:31,561
He ran Spain.

1361
01:18:32,703 --> 01:18:33,567
Spain?

1362
01:18:34,171 --> 01:18:35,536
The country. He ran it.

1363
01:18:35,739 --> 01:18:37,001
It was his job.

1364
01:18:37,240 --> 01:18:39,003
And then he died.

1365
01:18:39,242 --> 01:18:40,834
Just as well.

1366
01:18:41,078 --> 01:18:42,602
Milk or lemon?

1367
01:18:43,947 --> 01:18:47,212
She fell in love with
Generalissimo Franco.

1368
01:18:47,417 --> 01:18:49,476
Don't say that.
We don't know that for sure.

1369
01:18:49,686 --> 01:18:52,712
Who else could it have been?
It was probably around 1 960.

1370
01:18:52,923 --> 01:18:55,585
-Do you want some popcorn?
-I can't believe this.

1371
01:18:56,793 --> 01:18:58,761
It's not like
he was something normal...

1372
01:18:58,962 --> 01:19:01,362
...like a socialist, or an anarchist.

1373
01:19:01,598 --> 01:19:03,031
It happened in Spain.

1374
01:19:03,266 --> 01:19:05,496
People do stupid things
in foreign countries.

1375
01:19:05,702 --> 01:19:08,967
Absolutely. They buy leather jackets
for much more than they're worth.

1376
01:19:09,172 --> 01:19:12,198
But they don't fall in love
with fascist dictators.

1377
01:19:18,448 --> 01:19:21,349
Birdie is a very special person to me.

1378
01:19:21,551 --> 01:19:24,281
She is practically my surrogate mother.

1379
01:19:24,554 --> 01:19:27,352
-She's out of her mind.
-She is not.

1380
01:19:27,557 --> 01:19:29,149
I could never be with anyone...

1381
01:19:29,359 --> 01:19:31,884
...who doesn't take
politics as seriously as I do.

1382
01:19:32,462 --> 01:19:33,292
Do you mind?

1383
01:19:33,497 --> 01:19:34,862
A hot dog is singing.

1384
01:19:35,065 --> 01:19:37,727
You need quiet
while a hot dog is singing?

1385
01:19:41,405 --> 01:19:43,464
I have something to tell you, Frank.

1386
01:19:45,042 --> 01:19:46,236
I didn't vote.

1387
01:19:46,476 --> 01:19:47,272
What?

1388
01:19:47,477 --> 01:19:49,342
In the last mayoral election...

1389
01:19:49,546 --> 01:19:52,037
...when Rudy Giuliani was running
against Ruth Messinger.

1390
01:19:52,716 --> 01:19:54,377
I went to get a manicure.

1391
01:19:54,751 --> 01:19:56,810
And forgot to vote.

1392
01:19:57,220 --> 01:19:58,653
Since when do you get manicures?

1393
01:19:58,855 --> 01:20:01,983
I suppose you could never be with
a woman who got manicures?

1394
01:20:02,192 --> 01:20:03,819
Never mind. It's okay.

1395
01:20:04,161 --> 01:20:04,991
I forgive you.

1396
01:20:06,430 --> 01:20:07,658
You forgive me?

1397
01:20:16,540 --> 01:20:19,566
Excuse me, I'm sorry. Excuse me.

1398
01:20:20,710 --> 01:20:22,940
This has been a big week.
You're closing the store.

1399
01:20:23,180 --> 01:20:26,240
No, it's not that. Really, it's not.

1400
01:20:26,450 --> 01:20:29,419
I know. That was terrible of me.

1401
01:20:30,887 --> 01:20:31,911
What was terrible?

1402
01:20:32,122 --> 01:20:35,023
Jumping all over you
when I'm the one....

1403
01:20:36,460 --> 01:20:38,951
God, I don't even know how to say this.

1404
01:20:40,130 --> 01:20:41,427
What is it?

1405
01:20:42,299 --> 01:20:43,391
What?

1406
01:20:45,035 --> 01:20:47,560
You're a wonderful person, kathleen.

1407
01:20:47,771 --> 01:20:49,398
So are you.

1408
01:20:49,706 --> 01:20:52,300
And I'm so honored that you'd
want to be with me...

1409
01:20:52,509 --> 01:20:54,033
...because you would never be...

1410
01:20:54,244 --> 01:20:55,973
...with anyone...

1411
01:20:56,213 --> 01:20:58,044
...who wasn't truly worthy.

1412
01:20:58,248 --> 01:20:59,840
I feel exactly...

1413
01:21:00,050 --> 01:21:01,278
...the same way.

1414
01:21:01,718 --> 01:21:05,051
Don't say that.
That makes it worse.

1415
01:21:05,255 --> 01:21:06,279
What?

1416
01:21:08,258 --> 01:21:09,486
You don't love me.

1417
01:21:16,566 --> 01:21:17,555
Me either.

1418
01:21:18,568 --> 01:21:19,660
You don't love me?

1419
01:21:22,139 --> 01:21:23,231
No.

1420
01:21:23,473 --> 01:21:25,464
But we're so right for each other.

1421
01:21:25,675 --> 01:21:27,506
I know.

1422
01:21:30,347 --> 01:21:32,907
Well, is there someone else?

1423
01:21:33,950 --> 01:21:36,418
That woman on television, Sidney-Ann.

1424
01:21:38,088 --> 01:21:40,181
Nothing has happened or anything,
but....

1425
01:21:41,324 --> 01:21:43,121
Is she a Republican?

1426
01:21:43,426 --> 01:21:46,088
I can't help myself.

1427
01:21:55,138 --> 01:21:56,366
What about you?

1428
01:21:56,806 --> 01:21:58,671
Is there someone else?

1429
01:21:59,843 --> 01:22:01,003
No.

1430
01:22:02,179 --> 01:22:04,010
No. But...

1431
01:22:05,782 --> 01:22:08,444
...but there is the dream
of someone else.

1432
01:22:36,046 --> 01:22:38,480
Honey, grab a copy of
The Trumpet of the Swan.

1433
01:22:38,682 --> 01:22:40,547
This is a tragedy.

1434
01:22:42,052 --> 01:22:43,246
Are these chairs for sale?

1435
01:22:43,486 --> 01:22:44,817
Anything not nailed down.

1436
01:22:45,055 --> 01:22:46,545
Ten dollars, it's yours.

1437
01:22:46,756 --> 01:22:48,189
What are you going to do now?

1438
01:22:48,391 --> 01:22:52,293
I think I'll take some time.
I'm almost looking forward to it.

1439
01:22:52,495 --> 01:22:53,553
Good luck to you.

1440
01:22:55,765 --> 01:22:58,859
I came here every Saturday
when I was a little girl.

1441
01:22:59,069 --> 01:23:02,368
I remember when your mother
gave me Anne of Green Gables.

1442
01:23:02,572 --> 01:23:04,802
"Read it with a box of kleenex,"
she said.

1443
01:23:05,008 --> 01:23:06,498
That's what she told me.

1444
01:23:06,710 --> 01:23:07,677
Could someone help me?

1445
01:23:07,877 --> 01:23:09,105
She's looking down on you right now.

1446
01:23:09,713 --> 01:23:11,078
I'm sure she is.

1447
01:23:11,281 --> 01:23:13,909
Why don't we bomb Fox Books?

1448
01:25:03,026 --> 01:25:03,958
Do you have the "shoe" books?

1449
01:25:05,628 --> 01:25:06,959
The "shoe" books?

1450
01:25:07,297 --> 01:25:08,457
Who's the author?

1451
01:25:08,665 --> 01:25:09,654
I don't know.

1452
01:25:09,866 --> 01:25:12,494
My friend told me my daughter
has to read the "shoe" books...

1453
01:25:12,702 --> 01:25:14,567
...so here I am.

1454
01:25:14,804 --> 01:25:16,135
Noel Streatfeild.

1455
01:25:18,708 --> 01:25:21,871
Noel Streatfeild wrote
Ballet Shoes and Skating Shoes...

1456
01:25:22,078 --> 01:25:23,136
...and Theatre Shoes...

1457
01:25:23,346 --> 01:25:25,109
...and Dancing Shoes and....

1458
01:25:25,315 --> 01:25:28,079
I'd start with Ballet Shoes first,
it's my favorite.

1459
01:25:29,152 --> 01:25:30,380
Although Skating Shoes...

1460
01:25:30,587 --> 01:25:32,487
...is completely wonderful.

1461
01:25:33,656 --> 01:25:35,055
But it's out of print.

1462
01:25:35,992 --> 01:25:37,482
Streatfeild.

1463
01:25:38,395 --> 01:25:39,327
How do you spell that?

1464
01:25:41,164 --> 01:25:45,897
S-T-R-E-A-T-F-E-l-L-D.

1465
01:25:47,203 --> 01:25:48,693
Thank you.

1466
01:25:49,439 --> 01:25:52,101
Kathleen Kelly. I swear it was
like her name was in the air.

1467
01:25:52,675 --> 01:25:53,664
Just like that?

1468
01:25:53,877 --> 01:25:55,708
Everyone was talking about her today.

1469
01:25:55,912 --> 01:25:58,847
kathleen kelly and her "situation."

1470
01:25:59,048 --> 01:26:03,678
And I was thinking that she'd make
a great children's book editor.

1471
01:26:03,920 --> 01:26:05,478
What makes you think that?

1472
01:26:05,688 --> 01:26:06,586
Well...

1473
01:26:06,790 --> 01:26:08,348
...she knows everything.

1474
01:26:08,558 --> 01:26:11,527
She has flawless taste.
She's famous for it.

1475
01:26:11,728 --> 01:26:16,097
Salesmen swear by her. If she likes
the book, it sells. Period.

1476
01:26:16,366 --> 01:26:18,163
So you're going to offer her a job?

1477
01:26:18,368 --> 01:26:20,336
What else has she got to do?

1478
01:26:20,537 --> 01:26:22,027
Now that she's destitute.

1479
01:26:22,238 --> 01:26:23,432
Thanks to you.

1480
01:26:23,640 --> 01:26:25,369
I don't see her working for you.

1481
01:26:25,575 --> 01:26:26,405
Why not?

1482
01:26:26,609 --> 01:26:28,236
Because she lacks the killer instinct.

1483
01:26:28,445 --> 01:26:30,572
She's never fired anybody.
Look at that little shop of hers.

1484
01:26:30,780 --> 01:26:32,805
Those people have been there forever.

1485
01:26:33,149 --> 01:26:35,174
Till recently, when they all
lost their jobs.

1486
01:26:35,385 --> 01:26:37,046
Thanks to you.

1487
01:26:37,587 --> 01:26:39,612
Hold the elevator!

1488
01:26:42,225 --> 01:26:43,385
Mr. Fox.

1489
01:26:43,593 --> 01:26:45,254
Hello, Charlie.

1490
01:26:46,329 --> 01:26:47,887
I love how you've forgotten...

1491
01:26:48,097 --> 01:26:50,622
...you've had any role in her
current situation.

1492
01:26:50,834 --> 01:26:52,062
It's so obtuse.

1493
01:26:52,635 --> 01:26:54,603
It's so insensitive.

1494
01:26:54,804 --> 01:26:56,237
Reminds me of someone.

1495
01:26:56,439 --> 01:26:58,464
Who? Who does it remind me of?

1496
01:27:00,009 --> 01:27:01,306
Me.

1497
01:27:06,182 --> 01:27:07,240
What is going on?

1498
01:27:07,917 --> 01:27:08,906
Could be stuck.

1499
01:27:16,659 --> 01:27:17,751
What are you doing?

1500
01:27:18,761 --> 01:27:20,922
I hope this thing doesn't
plummet to the basement.

1501
01:27:21,931 --> 01:27:23,091
Can it do that?

1502
01:27:24,300 --> 01:27:26,768
It cannot plummet to the basement.

1503
01:27:27,670 --> 01:27:29,695
Hi, this is Joe Fox. Who's this?

1504
01:27:29,939 --> 01:27:30,928
Juan?

1505
01:27:31,374 --> 01:27:33,308
Juan, we are stuck in the elevator...

1506
01:27:33,510 --> 01:27:35,239
...between the sixth and seventh floor.

1507
01:27:35,445 --> 01:27:36,469
There's four of us.

1508
01:27:36,679 --> 01:27:38,112
If you don't get your ass...

1509
01:27:38,314 --> 01:27:39,576
...up here in two shakes...

1510
01:27:39,782 --> 01:27:42,376
...and get us the hell out of here...!

1511
01:27:43,786 --> 01:27:44,753
Listen...

1512
01:27:44,954 --> 01:27:46,148
...call the super...

1513
01:27:46,356 --> 01:27:47,550
...and then 9-1 -1 .

1514
01:27:49,092 --> 01:27:51,060
9-1 -1 .

1515
01:27:51,461 --> 01:27:53,361
The fire department, that's right.

1516
01:27:54,831 --> 01:27:56,560
Thank you very much.

1517
01:27:59,502 --> 01:28:00,434
Everyone should jump in the air.

1518
01:28:01,004 --> 01:28:01,834
What?

1519
01:28:02,772 --> 01:28:03,670
We jump...

1520
01:28:03,873 --> 01:28:06,740
...the elevator thinks
no one is here. And it opens.

1521
01:28:11,214 --> 01:28:12,203
One...

1522
01:28:12,415 --> 01:28:13,313
...two...

1523
01:28:13,516 --> 01:28:15,108
....three, jump.

1524
01:28:22,392 --> 01:28:23,825
If I ever get out of here...

1525
01:28:25,028 --> 01:28:27,360
...l'm going to start speaking
to my momma.

1526
01:28:28,765 --> 01:28:31,461
Wonder what she's doing
right this very minute?

1527
01:28:32,201 --> 01:28:33,964
If I ever get out of here...

1528
01:28:34,604 --> 01:28:36,538
...l'm marrying Orit.

1529
01:28:37,106 --> 01:28:38,596
I love her.

1530
01:28:38,975 --> 01:28:40,533
I should marry her.

1531
01:28:40,743 --> 01:28:42,438
I don't know what's been stopping me.

1532
01:28:49,218 --> 01:28:51,812
If I ever get out of here,
I'm having my eyes lasered.

1533
01:28:59,295 --> 01:29:01,024
If I ever get out of here....

1534
01:29:01,230 --> 01:29:02,492
Where are my Tic-Tacs?

1535
01:29:06,569 --> 01:29:07,900
What?

1536
01:29:10,773 --> 01:29:11,797
I came home tonight.

1537
01:29:12,008 --> 01:29:14,704
And got into the elevator
to go to my apartment.

1538
01:29:14,911 --> 01:29:17,971
An hour later
I got out of the elevator...

1539
01:29:18,181 --> 01:29:20,445
...and Brinkley and I moved out.

1540
01:29:20,650 --> 01:29:23,414
Suddenly everything had become clear.

1541
01:29:23,820 --> 01:29:25,253
It's a long story...

1542
01:29:25,688 --> 01:29:28,555
...full of the personal details
we avoid so carefully.

1543
01:29:28,758 --> 01:29:30,316
Let mejust say...

1544
01:29:30,760 --> 01:29:33,354
...there was a man sitting
in the elevator with me...

1545
01:29:33,696 --> 01:29:36,290
...who knew exactly what he wanted...

1546
01:29:36,866 --> 01:29:40,529
...and I found myself wishing
I were as lucky as he.

1547
01:29:43,940 --> 01:29:47,432
People are always telling you
that change is a good thing.

1548
01:29:47,810 --> 01:29:49,141
But all they're really saying...

1549
01:29:49,345 --> 01:29:51,609
...is that something you didn't
want to happen at all...

1550
01:29:52,048 --> 01:29:53,606
...has happened.

1551
01:29:54,884 --> 01:29:57,216
My store is closing this week.

1552
01:29:57,620 --> 01:29:59,178
I own a store.

1553
01:29:59,455 --> 01:30:01,150
Did I ever tell you that?

1554
01:30:01,624 --> 01:30:03,421
It's a lovely store.

1555
01:30:03,626 --> 01:30:06,254
And in a week it will be
something really depressing...

1556
01:30:06,462 --> 01:30:08,293
...like a Baby Gap.

1557
01:30:11,000 --> 01:30:12,729
Soon we'lljust be a memory.

1558
01:30:12,969 --> 01:30:15,130
In fact, someone,
some foolish person...

1559
01:30:15,338 --> 01:30:17,772
...will probably think
it's a tribute to this city.

1560
01:30:17,974 --> 01:30:19,532
The way it keeps changing on you.

1561
01:30:19,742 --> 01:30:22,734
Or the way you can never
count on it, or something.

1562
01:30:22,979 --> 01:30:25,243
I know, because that's
the sort of thing I'm always saying.

1563
01:30:25,481 --> 01:30:27,312
But the truth is...

1564
01:30:28,384 --> 01:30:30,079
...l'm heartbroken.

1565
01:30:32,555 --> 01:30:35,217
I feel as if a part of me has died...

1566
01:30:35,425 --> 01:30:38,155
...and my mother has died
all over again.

1567
01:30:40,997 --> 01:30:41,895
And no one...

1568
01:30:42,098 --> 01:30:43,929
...can ever make it right.

1569
01:32:48,858 --> 01:32:50,257
What happened?

1570
01:32:52,762 --> 01:32:54,059
Oh, hell.

1571
01:32:56,098 --> 01:32:56,996
How are you?

1572
01:32:57,200 --> 01:32:59,031
You know, Dad, you did pretty well.

1573
01:32:59,268 --> 01:33:00,360
At least you didn't marry her.

1574
01:33:00,603 --> 01:33:02,161
Welcome aboard.

1575
01:33:02,772 --> 01:33:04,433
It lasted awhile.

1576
01:33:20,456 --> 01:33:21,787
You know...

1577
01:33:22,758 --> 01:33:24,817
...l've stayed on this boat after...

1578
01:33:25,695 --> 01:33:26,923
...let's see...

1579
01:33:27,163 --> 01:33:28,596
...well, your mother.

1580
01:33:29,599 --> 01:33:31,157
Laurette, the ballet dancer.

1581
01:33:31,834 --> 01:33:32,892
My nanny.

1582
01:33:33,669 --> 01:33:35,068
She was the nanny?

1583
01:33:37,607 --> 01:33:39,165
I forgot that.

1584
01:33:40,009 --> 01:33:41,237
How ironic.

1585
01:33:41,444 --> 01:33:43,708
And then there was the ice skater.

1586
01:33:43,913 --> 01:33:44,937
Also my nanny.

1587
01:33:45,181 --> 01:33:46,011
Really?

1588
01:33:47,850 --> 01:33:49,818
Well, that's amazingly ironic.

1589
01:33:51,020 --> 01:33:52,180
And then there was Sybil.

1590
01:33:52,388 --> 01:33:53,719
The...

1591
01:33:54,056 --> 01:33:54,988
...it's an "A" word.

1592
01:33:55,191 --> 01:33:56,021
Astrologer.

1593
01:33:56,392 --> 01:33:57,950
Exactly. Yeah.

1594
01:33:58,461 --> 01:34:01,487
Whose moon turned out to be
in someone else's house.

1595
01:34:02,064 --> 01:34:03,258
Just like Gillian.

1596
01:34:04,901 --> 01:34:06,095
Gillian ran off with someone?

1597
01:34:06,302 --> 01:34:07,360
The nanny.

1598
01:34:08,104 --> 01:34:09,093
Nanny Maureen?

1599
01:34:13,809 --> 01:34:16,209
Gillian ran off with Nanny Maureen.

1600
01:34:16,779 --> 01:34:18,212
You got it.

1601
01:34:18,481 --> 01:34:20,540
It's incredibly ironic.

1602
01:34:20,816 --> 01:34:21,680
That's true.

1603
01:34:21,884 --> 01:34:23,818
No other word for it.

1604
01:34:24,220 --> 01:34:26,211
Well, who's better than us?

1605
01:34:26,722 --> 01:34:28,849
Father and son, together at last.

1606
01:34:29,325 --> 01:34:31,122
Who did you say you broke up with?

1607
01:34:31,727 --> 01:34:33,319
Patricia.

1608
01:34:33,562 --> 01:34:34,392
You met her.

1609
01:34:35,231 --> 01:34:36,061
Would I like her?

1610
01:34:38,734 --> 01:34:40,395
Just kidding, son.

1611
01:34:41,570 --> 01:34:43,902
Now, is this beautiful or what?

1612
01:34:44,907 --> 01:34:47,501
I'll be living out of a suitcase for...

1613
01:34:47,743 --> 01:34:48,710
...at least 3 weeks.

1614
01:34:49,245 --> 01:34:52,737
And then there's
the inevitable legal hassle.

1615
01:34:52,949 --> 01:34:54,382
More of your inheritance
down the drain.

1616
01:34:54,583 --> 01:34:56,050
Don't you worry about it.

1617
01:34:56,452 --> 01:34:57,441
I won't.

1618
01:34:57,653 --> 01:34:59,746
I'll just have to meet someone new,
that's all.

1619
01:34:59,956 --> 01:35:01,082
That's the easy part.

1620
01:35:01,290 --> 01:35:02,314
Right, yeah.

1621
01:35:02,525 --> 01:35:05,050
A snap to find
the one person in the world...

1622
01:35:05,261 --> 01:35:06,523
...who fills your heart with joy.

1623
01:35:06,762 --> 01:35:08,491
Well, don't be ridiculous.

1624
01:35:08,698 --> 01:35:11,428
Have I ever been with anybody
who fit that description?

1625
01:35:12,702 --> 01:35:13,532
Have you?

1626
01:35:41,297 --> 01:35:42,127
Who is it?

1627
01:35:44,233 --> 01:35:46,133
It's Joe Fox.

1628
01:35:47,837 --> 01:35:49,702
What are you doing here?

1629
01:35:52,074 --> 01:35:53,166
May I please come up?

1630
01:35:53,376 --> 01:35:54,502
No, I don't....

1631
01:35:54,710 --> 01:35:57,804
No, I don't really think that
that is a good idea, because...

1632
01:35:58,014 --> 01:35:59,481
...l have a...

1633
01:36:00,149 --> 01:36:01,639
...l have a terrible...

1634
01:36:01,884 --> 01:36:03,249
...cold.

1635
01:36:07,723 --> 01:36:08,781
Can you hear that?

1636
01:36:10,893 --> 01:36:13,919
I'm sniffling,
and I'm not really awake...

1637
01:36:14,163 --> 01:36:15,824
...and I'm taking echinacea...

1638
01:36:16,032 --> 01:36:18,091
...and vitamin C and sleeping
practically...

1639
01:36:18,334 --> 01:36:20,768
...24 hours a day.
I have a temperature.

1640
01:36:21,237 --> 01:36:25,139
And I think I'm contagious.
So I would...

1641
01:36:25,341 --> 01:36:28,174
...l would really appreciate it
if you would just go away.

1642
01:36:40,356 --> 01:36:42,017
Just a second!

1643
01:36:48,898 --> 01:36:51,423
Yes, just a second.

1644
01:37:04,146 --> 01:37:05,636
What are you doing here?

1645
01:37:05,981 --> 01:37:07,448
I heard you were sick...

1646
01:37:07,817 --> 01:37:09,375
...and I was worried.

1647
01:37:10,886 --> 01:37:11,944
And I wanted...

1648
01:37:12,154 --> 01:37:12,984
...to make--

1649
01:37:15,491 --> 01:37:17,220
Is there somebody here?

1650
01:37:18,494 --> 01:37:20,394
It's the Home Shopping Network.

1651
01:37:20,596 --> 01:37:22,928
You buy any of those
little porcelain dolls?

1652
01:37:23,132 --> 01:37:24,895
I was thinking about it.

1653
01:37:25,634 --> 01:37:27,067
You put me out of business.

1654
01:37:27,269 --> 01:37:28,201
Yes, I did.

1655
01:37:28,404 --> 01:37:29,837
Did you come to gloat?

1656
01:37:30,039 --> 01:37:31,063
To offer me a job?

1657
01:37:31,273 --> 01:37:32,205
I would never--

1658
01:37:32,408 --> 01:37:33,898
I have plans.
I have plenty of offers.

1659
01:37:34,110 --> 01:37:35,737
You know, I got offered a job by--

1660
01:37:35,978 --> 01:37:36,910
By my former....

1661
01:37:37,113 --> 01:37:38,080
Your former?

1662
01:37:39,081 --> 01:37:39,979
We broke up.

1663
01:37:40,182 --> 01:37:42,548
That's too bad. You were
so perfect for each other.

1664
01:37:46,755 --> 01:37:48,188
I don't mean to say things like that.

1665
01:37:48,424 --> 01:37:49,721
No matter what you've done...

1666
01:37:49,925 --> 01:37:52,052
...there's no excuse for my
saying anything like that.

1667
01:37:52,261 --> 01:37:53,489
But every time I see you--

1668
01:37:53,696 --> 01:37:56,028
Things like that just
fly out of your mouth.

1669
01:37:58,434 --> 01:37:59,696
I brought you flowers.

1670
01:38:03,672 --> 01:38:04,502
Thank you.

1671
01:38:09,945 --> 01:38:12,209
Why don't I just
put these in some water?

1672
01:38:13,682 --> 01:38:14,512
You're sick.

1673
01:38:14,717 --> 01:38:15,547
You should sit down.

1674
01:38:21,457 --> 01:38:22,890
I need a vase?

1675
01:38:23,826 --> 01:38:25,851
Above the refrigerator.

1676
01:38:26,295 --> 01:38:28,786
There it is. Obviously.

1677
01:38:29,965 --> 01:38:32,661
George says hello, by the way.

1678
01:38:34,403 --> 01:38:35,961
He told me you were sick.

1679
01:38:36,305 --> 01:38:37,203
How is George?

1680
01:38:39,074 --> 01:38:41,133
He's great, really great.

1681
01:38:41,343 --> 01:38:43,402
He's revolutionizing the place.

1682
01:38:44,213 --> 01:38:45,612
You can't work in his department...

1683
01:38:45,814 --> 01:38:47,406
...unless you have a Ph.D.
in Children's Literature.

1684
01:38:48,651 --> 01:38:50,278
I love daisies.

1685
01:38:51,554 --> 01:38:52,384
You told me.

1686
01:38:52,588 --> 01:38:54,021
They're so friendly.

1687
01:38:54,223 --> 01:38:56,555
Don't you think daisies
are the friendliest flower?

1688
01:38:57,826 --> 01:38:58,815
I do.

1689
01:38:59,929 --> 01:39:01,089
When did you break up?

1690
01:39:02,431 --> 01:39:03,659
Couple of weeks ago.

1691
01:39:04,366 --> 01:39:06,994
Everyone is breaking up. You. Me.

1692
01:39:07,203 --> 01:39:09,865
This other person I know broke up
with someone in an elevator...

1693
01:39:10,105 --> 01:39:13,871
...or after it,
or just outside it, or....

1694
01:39:14,109 --> 01:39:15,838
It got stuck....

1695
01:39:16,345 --> 01:39:19,781
When I saw you at the coffee place,
I was waiting for him.

1696
01:39:20,015 --> 01:39:21,175
And I was....

1697
01:39:21,450 --> 01:39:22,781
Charming.

1698
01:39:23,219 --> 01:39:24,652
I was not charming.

1699
01:39:24,853 --> 01:39:26,844
Well, you looked charming. Tea?

1700
01:39:27,056 --> 01:39:28,114
Yes.

1701
01:39:28,757 --> 01:39:31,191
I was upset and horrible.

1702
01:39:32,027 --> 01:39:33,289
Honey?

1703
01:39:33,963 --> 01:39:35,260
I was the horrible one.

1704
01:39:35,464 --> 01:39:37,022
Well, that's true.

1705
01:39:37,233 --> 01:39:39,030
But I have no excuse.

1706
01:39:40,536 --> 01:39:42,527
I see what you're saying.

1707
01:39:43,472 --> 01:39:44,666
That's interesting.

1708
01:39:44,873 --> 01:39:47,034
Whereas I am a horrible person...

1709
01:39:47,243 --> 01:39:50,440
...therefore I have no choice
but to be horrible.

1710
01:39:50,646 --> 01:39:51,670
That's what you're saying.

1711
01:39:53,315 --> 01:39:54,145
But that's all right.

1712
01:39:54,383 --> 01:39:56,908
That's all right. I put you
out of business, so...

1713
01:39:57,586 --> 01:39:59,178
...you're entitled to hate me.

1714
01:40:00,656 --> 01:40:01,486
I don't hate you.

1715
01:40:03,092 --> 01:40:04,992
But you'll never forgive me.

1716
01:40:05,728 --> 01:40:06,592
Just like Elizabeth.

1717
01:40:07,096 --> 01:40:07,926
Who?

1718
01:40:08,597 --> 01:40:09,495
Elizabeth Bennet...

1719
01:40:09,698 --> 01:40:12,895
...in Pride and Prejudice.
She was too proud.

1720
01:40:13,269 --> 01:40:14,736
I thought you hated
Pride and Prejudice.

1721
01:40:14,937 --> 01:40:17,497
Or was she too prejudiced...

1722
01:40:17,740 --> 01:40:20,208
...and Mr. Darcy is too proud?

1723
01:40:20,442 --> 01:40:21,807
Well, I can't remember.

1724
01:40:28,083 --> 01:40:29,948
It wasn't personal.

1725
01:40:30,286 --> 01:40:33,585
What is that supposed to mean?
I'm so sick of that.

1726
01:40:33,822 --> 01:40:37,258
All that means
is that it wasn't personal to you.

1727
01:40:37,459 --> 01:40:39,120
But it was personal to me.

1728
01:40:39,328 --> 01:40:41,592
It's personal to a lot of people.

1729
01:40:41,797 --> 01:40:43,594
What is so wrong with being personal?

1730
01:40:46,135 --> 01:40:47,534
Nothing.

1731
01:40:47,770 --> 01:40:50,933
Whatever else anything is,
it ought to begin by being personal.

1732
01:40:55,144 --> 01:40:57,612
My head is starting to get fuzzy.

1733
01:41:02,951 --> 01:41:04,885
Why did you stop by again?
I forget.

1734
01:41:06,455 --> 01:41:07,752
I wanted to be your friend.

1735
01:41:11,126 --> 01:41:13,219
I knew it wasn't possible.

1736
01:41:14,296 --> 01:41:17,459
What can I say? Sometimes a guy
just wants the impossible.

1737
01:41:27,309 --> 01:41:29,243
Can I ask you a question?

1738
01:41:29,545 --> 01:41:30,705
What?

1739
01:41:32,514 --> 01:41:35,176
What happened with that guy
at the caf?

1740
01:41:36,051 --> 01:41:37,211
Nothing.

1741
01:41:37,419 --> 01:41:39,216
But you're crazy about him?

1742
01:41:40,656 --> 01:41:41,645
Yes, I am.

1743
01:41:41,857 --> 01:41:44,826
Why don't you run off with him?
What are you waiting for?

1744
01:41:47,663 --> 01:41:49,528
I don't actually know him.

1745
01:41:50,432 --> 01:41:51,262
Really?

1746
01:41:53,836 --> 01:41:55,360
I only know him through the....

1747
01:41:57,373 --> 01:41:58,738
You're not going to believe this.

1748
01:41:58,941 --> 01:42:00,670
Let me guess.

1749
01:42:01,176 --> 01:42:02,541
Through the lnternet?

1750
01:42:03,846 --> 01:42:04,676
Yes.

1751
01:42:08,717 --> 01:42:09,706
"You've...

1752
01:42:10,185 --> 01:42:11,277
...got mail."

1753
01:42:15,124 --> 01:42:16,648
Those are very powerful words.

1754
01:42:21,730 --> 01:42:22,890
I'm happy for him.

1755
01:42:24,967 --> 01:42:26,628
Although....

1756
01:42:27,903 --> 01:42:29,962
Could I just make a little suggestion?

1757
01:42:30,572 --> 01:42:31,732
What?

1758
01:42:32,274 --> 01:42:33,468
I think...

1759
01:42:34,309 --> 01:42:36,038
...you should meet him.

1760
01:42:36,445 --> 01:42:38,208
No, wait, I take that back.

1761
01:42:39,915 --> 01:42:41,906
Why would you want to meet
somebody you're crazy about?

1762
01:42:43,051 --> 01:42:46,418
I hardly think I need to take
advice from a person who--

1763
01:42:48,957 --> 01:42:51,357
Now I can see that I
bring out the worst in you.

1764
01:42:51,593 --> 01:42:54,221
But let me just help
you to not say something...

1765
01:42:54,430 --> 01:42:56,398
...you're just going to
torture yourself about...

1766
01:42:56,598 --> 01:42:58,930
...for years to come.

1767
01:43:11,947 --> 01:43:13,812
I hope you feel better soon.

1768
01:43:15,617 --> 01:43:17,949
It would be a shame to miss
New York in the spring.

1769
01:43:22,124 --> 01:43:23,751
Thank you for the daisies.

1770
01:43:34,770 --> 01:43:35,759
Well...

1771
01:43:35,971 --> 01:43:37,438
...you take care.

1772
01:43:38,874 --> 01:43:39,932
I will.

1773
01:43:41,376 --> 01:43:42,240
Goodbye.

1774
01:43:44,146 --> 01:43:45,511
Goodbye.

1775
01:44:02,464 --> 01:44:04,489
I've been thinking about this...

1776
01:44:04,867 --> 01:44:06,835
...and I think we should meet.

1777
01:44:13,709 --> 01:44:15,336
We should meet.

1778
01:44:15,978 --> 01:44:17,741
And we will meet.

1779
01:44:18,313 --> 01:44:22,181
But I'm in the middle
of a project that needs...

1780
01:44:27,489 --> 01:44:29,013
...tweaking.

1781
01:44:48,877 --> 01:44:50,401
Some tweaking?

1782
01:44:50,946 --> 01:44:52,937
A project that needed...

1783
01:44:53,215 --> 01:44:54,182
..."tweaking."

1784
01:44:54,383 --> 01:44:57,250
-Yeah, that's what he said.
-T-W-E-A-k-l-N-G?

1785
01:44:57,452 --> 01:44:58,578
-Tweaking.
-That's what he said.

1786
01:44:59,288 --> 01:45:02,223
It sounds to me like he's married...

1787
01:45:02,591 --> 01:45:03,558
...3 kids.

1788
01:45:03,759 --> 01:45:05,124
That's a terrible thing to say.

1789
01:45:05,327 --> 01:45:06,589
He couldn't possibly be married.

1790
01:45:06,795 --> 01:45:08,194
How do you know?

1791
01:45:08,397 --> 01:45:10,695
Have you said, "Are you married?"
Have you written to him?

1792
01:45:10,899 --> 01:45:13,424
No, I'm not going to-- No.

1793
01:45:14,803 --> 01:45:18,295
I know this is probably
a little late to be asking, but...

1794
01:45:19,374 --> 01:45:20,807
...are you married?

1795
01:45:24,379 --> 01:45:25,778
Am I married?

1796
01:45:25,981 --> 01:45:28,040
What kind of question is that?

1797
01:45:28,584 --> 01:45:30,142
How can you ask me that?

1798
01:45:30,385 --> 01:45:31,511
Don't you know me at all?

1799
01:45:31,753 --> 01:45:33,653
Wait, I get it.

1800
01:45:34,289 --> 01:45:36,655
Your friends are telling you
the reason we haven't met...

1801
01:45:36,892 --> 01:45:38,985
...is that I'm married.
Am I right?

1802
01:45:40,529 --> 01:45:41,689
So he didn't answer the question.

1803
01:45:41,897 --> 01:45:42,829
Yes, he did.

1804
01:45:43,031 --> 01:45:43,963
-He did not.
-He did too.

1805
01:45:44,199 --> 01:45:45,996
He did. He nailed me.

1806
01:45:46,201 --> 01:45:47,793
He knew exactly what I was after...

1807
01:45:48,036 --> 01:45:50,163
...which is, by the way,
exactly like him.

1808
01:45:50,372 --> 01:45:52,101
He did not answer the question,
did he?

1809
01:45:54,443 --> 01:45:55,239
No.

1810
01:45:57,446 --> 01:45:59,004
Maybe he's fat.

1811
01:46:00,382 --> 01:46:02,282
He's fat. He's a fatty.

1812
01:46:02,618 --> 01:46:03,778
I don't care about that.

1813
01:46:03,986 --> 01:46:05,851
You don't care that he's so fat...

1814
01:46:06,054 --> 01:46:09,046
...he has to be removed
from his house by a crane.

1815
01:46:09,291 --> 01:46:10,121
You don't care.

1816
01:46:10,325 --> 01:46:11,758
That is very unlikely.

1817
01:46:11,994 --> 01:46:14,326
That is completely ridiculous.

1818
01:46:14,896 --> 01:46:15,920
So what's his handle?

1819
01:46:19,835 --> 01:46:21,598
I'm not going to write him.

1820
01:46:21,837 --> 01:46:23,737
You think I'm going to e-mail him?

1821
01:46:26,141 --> 01:46:27,335
All right, N-Y-1 -5-2.

1822
01:46:28,010 --> 01:46:30,740
N-Y-1 -5-2? 1 52.

1823
01:46:30,946 --> 01:46:33,039
He's 1 52 years old.

